<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Underlines Full World Response to African Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Friday stressed "the need for a comprehensive
response" to a challenge in Africa in order to bring an end to
both conflicts and poverty in the war-ravaged continent.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the U.N. chief was addressing the plenum
session of the General Assembly, which opened a debate on a report
by Annan, who analyzed in April the internal and external causes
of conflicts in Africa and how to achieve sustainable development
in the continent.
</P>
<P>
"I emphasized the need for a comprehensive response to a
challenge which has many roots and facets," Annan said,
"Specifically, I called for the promotion of investment and
economic growth, of ensuring adequate levels of international aid,
of reducing debt burdens and opening international markets to
Africa's products."
</P>
<P>
Annan, the first U.N. secretary-general from black Africa, said
that "while the burden of responsibility for Africa's fate lies in
African hands, Africa's development partners can also do more and
do better to assist Africa's struggle for lasting prosperityly."
</P>
<P>
Annan's Friday remarks once again highlight the growing U.N.
concerns over security and development in Africa and increasing
U.N. efforts, together with African regional groups including the
Organization of African Unity, to end conflicts in the continent.
</P>
<P>
Africa has witnessed more than 30 wars since 1970. Annan said
in his report that a quarter of African countries was plagued by
conflicts last year, which caused more than half of the world's
casualties. Of these deaths created by conflicts, some 90 percent
are civilians, most of whom are women and children.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Annan also added urgency of the challenge in a
time "when the global economy is facing serious threats and when
millions the world over have been thrown back into a life of
poverty after years of struggle and success."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Annan also briefed the session on his meeting last
Tuesday with visiting U.S. Secretary of Treasury Robert Rubin,
during which the two sides discussed the current global economic
crisis, in particular the crisis of globalization and the United
Nations response.
</P>
<P>
"I also urged immediate and dramatic action to the debt
situation facing Africa's poorest nations, particularly in these
dark days of global economic crisis," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The crisis is now a threat not only to Africa's prospects for
growth, but to Africa's attempts to secure free and democratic
societies," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council adopted a resolution at the end
of consideration of this report in September, with a determination
to help African countries improve the conflict-preventive
capabilities and better investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from such countries as Argentina, Austria,
Burkina Faso and Malaysia also took the floor in the debate
session, voicing their support to find "the African solution to
African problems." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Urges People to Promote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni called on his countrymen Friday afternoon to act to
promote security in the country.
</P>
<P>
He made the appeal when addressing the nation at a celebration
here marking the 36th anniversary of Uganda's independence from
British rule.
</P>
<P>
"Our security can best be assured through the collective
action of the majority of the population. I ask each and every
Ugandan to be each other's keeper," he urged.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, terrorism was labeled as a weapon of the weak,
the dispirited and the cowardly.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorism can be defeated if we all become sensitive to our
security and alert the authorities to anything and anyone likely
to jeopardize security. Security is too important to be left
only to the security organs," he explained.
</P>
<P>
"It is a sign of stability in the politics of the country to
see that our opponents have for some time now been resorting to
terrorism," added the 53-year-old president.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the opponents resort to terrorism because
they can neither successfully challenge the government through
the ballot box nor take on the government militarily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Museveni said, the security organs should be alert
and utilize fully the information offered by the general public.
</P>
<P>
Although it is important to set timetables, the president
wishes to assure his fellow Ugandans that the lingering
insurgency and banditry in both northern and western parts of the
country will be history in the goodness of time.
</P>
<P>
He promised that the government will do everything possible to
stop infiltration from Sudan and to eradicate all bandit hideouts
in Rwenzori mountains in western Uganda and eastern Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
All that the public should do is to be on constant alert and
contribute information which may lead to arrest of criminals and
terrorists. Only general mobilization can eventually wipe out
terrorism from the country, the president said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
