<HEADLINE> Davenport Claims World No. 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, October (Xinhua) -- Lindsay Davenport claimed the No. 1
ranking in women's tennis Friday when Martina Hingis was beaten
at the Porsche Grand Prix in Filderstadt, Germany, said reports
reaching here.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, who needed to win to hold off the charging American in
the computer rankings, lost to Belgium's Dominique Van Roost 3-6,
7-6 (7-4), 6-4 in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
Davenport, the U.S. Open champion, will officially end the
Swiss teenager's 80-week reign at the top in the new rankings to
be released Monday.
</P>
<P>
Van Roost, ranked 12th, constantly caught the 18-year-old
Hingis flatfooted or moving in the wrong direction with her
disguised strokes, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Davenport would have taken away Hingis' top ranking, even if
the Swiss teenager had won, if she beat France's Nathalie Tauziat
in her quarterfinal match to be played later in the day.
</P>
<P>
Spain's Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario, the fourth seed, became the
first player to reach the semifinals after she rallied from 1-4
down in the second set to beat Lisa Raymond of the United States,
1-6, 7-5, 6-2.  
</P>
</TEXT>
