<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Rejects Turkish Accusation over PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Ministry has
expressed "astonishment" at a statement made by Turkish ambassador
in Amman alleging that Iraq has contacts with the Kurdish Worker's
Party (PKK), outlawed in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency Friday, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman termed the Turkish allegations as
groundless.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq deplores the Turkish statements and it (Iraq) would like
to remind Turkey that the presence of PKK elements in northern
Iraq was caused by the abnormal situation created in 1991 by the
Americans, British and Turks themselves," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since the Gulf War in which Iraqi troops were defeated, U.S.
and British aircrafts have been using Turkish military base to
enforce a no-fly zone in northern Iraq, under the name of
protecting Iraqi Kurds there. Baghdad has been mainly ineffective
in its control over the region.
</P>
<P>
Fighting since 1984 for autonomy in southeast Turkey, PKK
militants often launched cross-border attacks on targets inside
Turkey from northern Iraq where they found shelter after the Gulf
War ended.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman criticized Turkey for fresh military
incursions into northern Iraq under the pretext of tracking down
the Kurdish opposition movement.
</P>
<P>
On October 2 over 10,000 Turkish armed troops crossed into
northern Iraq with the support of Turkish air force.
</P>
<P>
While calling on Turkey to pull out its troops from Iraq's
territory immediately, the spokesman alleged that Turkey has
contacts with Iraqi Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
"We find that Turkey continues its contacts with Iraqi Kurdish
rebels and provides them with assistance and facilities, a matter
which directly contributes to perpetuating the abnormal status in
northern Iraq and spreading instability in the region," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He urges Turkey to reconsider its position towards the
abnormal situation in northern Iraq, saying "the return of the
central authority is the sole guarantee to establish security and
stability in this region."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman warned Turkey against "running after the mirage
of American dubious schemes" which he said will never solve the
Kurdish problem inside Turkey, warning "if Turkey continues with
its double-standard policy, it will sustain heavy losses."
</P>
<P>
"Paying no heed to the good neighborly relations with Iraq in
particular and with the Arab nation in general contradicts the
national interests of the Muslim Turkish people," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
