<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberia Apologizes for Shooting at U.S. Embassy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Liberian government Friday
expressed "regrets" to the U.S. government for September's
shooting incident at the U.S. embassy in Monrovia, and called for
a joint probe of the matter, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
"The government regrets any injury persons protected under
international law may have suffered, as it considers the safety
of these persons to be of paramount importance and indispensable
to the conduct of the international relations," it said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Liberian security forces shot into the U.S. embassy on
September 19, while pursuing former faction leader Roosevelt
Johnson and his supporters, who were seeking refuge in the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
Johnson was declared wanted by the Liberian government on
treason charges after he escaped arrest attempts by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Two of his aides were reportedly shot dead at the embassy
while two American citizens working in the embassy were wounded
in the shooting accident.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government had closed its embassy in Monrovia and
demanded an apology from Liberia. It also demanded a thorough
investigation of the incident by the Liberian government.
</P>
<P>
But the Liberian government said in the statement that it did
not sanction any firing at the embassy or at American citizens.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Liberia is fully aware of its obligations
and responsibility under international law, and shall continue to
provide maximum security and protection to all diplomatic
missions and their personnel, including the U.S. embassy," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The Liberian government also invited the U.S. to join its
investigators to probe the incident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
