<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Hopes to Set Up E. African Community Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni expressed his hope Friday afternoon that the East
African Community (EAC) be established in April, 1999.
</P>
<P>
When addressing the mass gathered to celebrate the 36th
anniversary of Uganda's independence, the president said the
government is strongly committed to East African Cooperation and
is looking forward to signing the treaty to set up the EAC soon.
</P>
<P>
He outlined the main tasks the government is seriously
undertaking at the moment so as to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
They include: harmonization of fiscal and monetary policies,
easing of border movements of people and goods, updating
investment code, according national status to east Africans
investing in an EAC country other than his own, establishing
regional investment promotion center by 2000, establishing
industrial standards and introducing inter-state passes and
passports.
</P>
<P>
Only when these preparations have been made can the EAC be
materialized in the real sense of the word, he said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania have been cooperating closely for
political, economical and cultural development in the region.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said in his one-day visit to
Uganda Tuesday that his country is improving its infrastructure
to create a better investment environment for the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
