<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Forecasts Success of Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese people will exhibit
resolute determination and ensure the success of the Three Gorges
Project, according to Li Peng, chairman of the Standing Committee
of the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project was initiated on the basis of thorough
scientific investigations. The project was approved by the NPC and
has the full support of Chinese citizens, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
Li, a member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau
of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central Committee, made the
remarks during an October 3-9 fact-finding tour of the Three
Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
Li also visited Fuling, Wanzhou, Yunyang, and Zigui where he
solicited the opinions of local residents and examined the
relocation program.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River was blocked last year to build the dam and
the second phase of the project, the world's largest water
conservation project, is progressing smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Some 150,000 people had been relocated by the end of August,
and an additional 550,000 people will be relocated during the
second phase.
</P>
<P>
Li said relocation and resettlement progressing are operating
smoothly, and specifically cited the extensive efforts of
Chongqing Municipality and the Hubei provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project has entered into a crucial stage, and
top priority must focus of project quality, according to Li.
</P>
<P>
The project will yield great comprehensive benefits for flood
control, power generation and shipping, said Li.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that the primary function will center
on effective flood control by the year 2003. This summer's
devastating floods provided ample proof of the urgency and
importance of constructing the project, said Li.
</P>
<P>
Environmentally-sound agriculture can be developed in the dam
area and administrative affairs must be managed in accordance with
the law, said Li, adding that standard environmental protection
practices and relocation efforts can be achieved by adopting
regional law and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Li has visited the Three Gorges area on seven fact-finding
tours since the NPC approved the project in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
