<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Expects Higher Economic Growth This year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus economy is expected to
grow by 4.5 percent in real terms in 1998, compared with 2.5
percent last year, the Planning Bureau said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was based on the expectation of political
stability in the country, robust tourism, increased external
demand and recovery of domestic demand, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
A report issued by the bureau said that Cyprus' economy has
begun to pick up since mid-1997 and maintained a growing momentum
in the first half of this year thanks to the tourism boom and the
good performance of the services sector, whose earnings make up 73
percent of the country's gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The report quoted statistics as showing that during the first
half of this year, foreign traveler arrivals increased by nearly 9
percent to reach 1.1 million.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, over 2 million foreign travelers visited the island,
bringing an income of about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars, or 20
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The construction industry, which underwent a grave slump last
year, showed some signs of recovery in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector is also gaining its fizz thanks to
higher demand at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
Economy revival helped to keep unemployment rate at a low level
of 3.3 percent of the economically active population at the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the overall balance of payments for the first
seven months of this year was in surplus, estimated provisionally
at 28.4 million Cyprus pounds (about 56.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
This was brought about by a significant rise in net capital
inflows in July, associated with a government bond issue under the
European medium-term note program, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Multi-Party Talks Postponed to Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Lesotho government,
opposition parties and Southern African Development Community
(SADC) mediators will hold a new round of talks next Wednesday,
South African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamady said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The talks were due originally on Monday. The decision to
postpone Monday's meeting was made in consultation with the
parties involved, said Mufamadi, who heads the SADC team.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's office said
Thursday that the Lesotho opposition party alliance was ready to
report back on a SADC proposal for the formation of a
transitional structure at the coming talks.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the SADC proposal, a transitional committee would
help create conditions conducive to the holding of free and fair
elections, Mufamadi said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed committee would comprise one or two members from
each party taking part in the election, and would ensure equal
treatment for all political parties by state-owned broadcasting
and information services in the period leading up to the
election.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki's spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said the SADC was fairly
optimistic that political parties in Lesotho were committed to
moving their country out of its present political impasse.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho held a general election on May 23, but opposition
parties claimed the election was rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy.
</P>
<P>
A national unrest occurred since early August. The government
of the mountain kingdom became paralyzed when some young officers
and soldiers tried in mid-September to overthrow the cabinet led
by Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of Mosisili's government, South Africa and
Botswana sent their troops in the name of the SADC on September
22 to help restore law and order in Lesotho. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
