<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Conviction Rate in Rape Cases in S. Africa: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa has the
highest rape rate in the world. However, only one rapist was
convicted for every 400 women raped last year, a survey has
found.
</P>
<P>
Following interviews with 4,000 women, the survey found that
for every 400 women raped, 272 reported the crime to police.
</P>
<P>
Of these reports, 17 became cases to be investigated, one of
the dockets was lost, police referred five to the court and only
one rapist was convicted.
</P>
<P>
The survey was a collaboration by Johannesburg's southern
metropolitan local council, police, a non-governmental
organization and community organizations, South African Press
Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
However, SAPA did not say when the survey was conducted.
</P>
<P>
Professor Neil Anderson, who was in charge of the survey, said
the statistics highlighted a need for the judiciary and the
police to increase the number of rape cases going through the
legal system and harsher penalties for perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutors and police said the low conviction rate was partly
because about 50 percent of rape victims withdrew their cases
from court. Reasons for this included that women were often
poorly prepared to deal with the court system.
</P>
<P>
Another major finding was that most sexual violence in
southern Johannesburg happened in the home, with 60 percent of
rapists known to the victim and one in four rapists being a
family member.
</P>
<P>
This meant that traditional policing methods and increased
police presence on the streets would not alleviate the problem,
SAPA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africans Urged to Act Immediately Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 9 (Xinhua) -- South African Deputy
President Thabo Mbeki Friday launched a national campaign here
against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address, Mbeki said South Africa had for too
many years allowed the HIV virus to spread at a rate which was
one of the fastest in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Every single day a further 1,500 people in South Africa get
infected. To date, more than three million people have been
infected," he said.
</P>
<P>
By allowing the pandemic to spread, South Africa faced the
danger that half of the country's youth would not reach
adulthood, Mbeki said.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest census, South Africa has a population
of about 40 million.
</P>
<P>
To curb the deadly disease, Mbeki said the government would
"mobilize all possible resources to spread the message of
prevention, to offer support to those infected and affected, to
de-stigmatize HIV and AIDS, and to continue our search for a
medical solution".
</P>
<P>
Representatives of various sectors in South Africa attended
the launching ceremony in Johannesburg, and pledged support for
the campaign.
</P>
<P>
In a press conference, South African Health Minister Nkosazana
Zuma also urged all people in the country to make sustained
efforts to wipe out AIDS.
</P>
<P>
She said drugs were available on the market to prolong the
lives of people infected with HIV/AIDS, but these medicines were
expensive.
</P>
<P>
The minister called on the public to join the government in
pressurizing drug manufacturers to reduce prices.
</P>
<P>
As part of the campaign, South African national flags were
flown at half-mast Friday on all government buildings, including
parliament and foreign missions abroad, in line with a directive
from President Nelson Mandela, government sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
