<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM Says Syria Supports Kurdish Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem has sent letters to his Arab counterparts, saying Syria is
supporting the Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
A Turkish Foreign Ministry official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that Cem pointed out that Syria was trying to
provoke Arab states against Turkey with misleading information,
the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
But he said that there are very positive relations between
Turkey and Arab states, and no one will have the power to disrupt
these relations.
</P>
<P>
In the letters, Cem said that Damascus has extended facilities
to the Kurdish rebels, which have been fighting since 1984 for an
independent homeland in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said that Turkey has warned Syria many times diplomatically,
but Syria failed to respond to these warnings.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Syria and Turkey have always been troublesome.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of harboring the PKK, while
Syrian, denying the charges, repeatedly voiced its concern and
anger over Turkey's close military ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has intensified its vocal attacks on Syria and, for the
first time, massed heavy troops along Syrian borders late last
week.
</P>
<P>
It issued an ultimatum to Syria this week, threatening to
uproot the alleged Kurdish camps in Syria by force if Syria fails
to stop supporting the PKK within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's warlike rhetoric has aroused fears of a conflict that
may spill over the region.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi were making efforts to try to ease the tension
between the two neighbors and attain a peaceful solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
