<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De-Mining in Angola Paralyzed by Tension of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The de-mining activities in
Angola have been virtually paralyzed due to the stalemate in the
peace process and the increasing tension of war in the country.
</P>
<P>
The increasing military moves taken by the opposition National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) has posed
great threat to the safety of de-mining personnel, hence bringing
the country's landmine clearing activities to a standstill, said
Helder Cruz, head of National Institute for Removal of Obstacles
and Explosives.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks here Friday to representatives of donor
countries assisting the de-mining operations in the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, there were 19 de-mining teams working
across the country, but now the number is reduced to eight, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cruz appealed to the international community to take up
effective measures to force UNITA Chairman Jonas Savimbi to give
up war and disarm his forces as prescribed by the Lusaka Protocol
signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
He also called for more international aid in clearing
landmines in Angola so as to eliminate its scourg to the human
society as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the leading countries which laid the most
landmines. Statistics from a U.N. agency showed that a total of
11 million mines had been laid during the 30-year
anti-colonialism and civil war.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, over 170,000 landmines have been cleared in the
southern African country, making 4,429-km-long highways free of
mines.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has donated five million U.S. Dollars to Angola
this year for de-mining. Similarly, the United States also
provided nearly two-million-Dollar assistance in this regard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
