<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Strike Activation Expected Over Weekend: NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- NATO was expected to issue the
order that would activate the phased air strikes it has threatened
for almost seven months, an alliance official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
But the issuance of activation order does not immediately lead
to actual air-borne attacks, the official hinted after the day's
two sessions of the North Atlantic Council, the decision-making
body of the western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors are due to meet for certain on Saturday and on
Sunday as well if need arises, the official said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"Decision is imminent and decision can be taken quickly," said
the official who explained that the activation order would
authorize the supreme commander of Europe to deliver the planned
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The order to be issued covers five phases of the air-borne
attack NATO has planned as an option to bring Belgrade to full
compliance with the demands of the international community.
</P>
<P>
Each of the phase needs a case-by-case authorization from the
North Atlantic Council while the phase that already gets the green
light remains valid during the authorized period of time in the
hands of the supreme commander of Europe, now United States
General Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
But the official did not clarify how long the valid duration of
authorization for each phase lasts.
</P>
<P>
He only said that the mechanism of re-authorization is designed
to put the phased air strikes under political control for the role
of engagement and targeting in different phases.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Australia reportedly started
evacuating non-essential embassy staffs and the families of
diplomats from Belgrade for fear that they would be taken hostage
once air strikes are underway as it was the case in 1994 when NATO
missiles hit Serbian targets in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO has amassed a total of 340 warplanes including 260 from
the United States that provided the NATO air strike operation with
two B2 Stealth bombers and six B52 bombers.
</P>
<P>
The same official said that NATO ambassadors also met their
Russian counterpart during the day and the NATO-Russia Permanent
Joint Council (PJC) served as the third Kosovo-related
consultation of late and the second within the week.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the PJC proved to the fact that
NATO-Russian cooperation is needed in crises like that in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"NATO and Russia came close together in that the Russians
agreed that compliance has to be verifiable and both the Serbians
and Kosovars have to keep their promises," said he.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU to Hold Meeting on Displaced People in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of African
Unity (OAU) announced Friday that a regional meeting will be held
here on October 12 to 15 on enhancing the participation of
conflict-affected population in reconstruction and peace
building.
</P>
<P>
An OAU press release issued here said the meeting will focus
on returnees, refugees and internally displaced women and
children and their participation both as contributors to and
beneficiaries of this aspect of the peace process and how that
participation can be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that the general objective of the meeting
will include the adoption of a plan of action for reconstruction,
rehabilitation and ensuring peace building for the populations
affected by conflicts, particularly returnees, refugees and
internally displaced women and children.
</P>
<P>
The plan of action will constitute concrete and implementable
programs and project proposals which facilitate the
re-integration of vulnerable groups in the resettlement and
development process of countries emerging from conflicts, said
the release.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will be attended by a broad spectrum of
participants from international organizations, OAU member states,
interest groups, observers as well as representatives of women's
peace movements, according to the press release.
</P>
<P>
African refugee problem has been very grim in the world.
According to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR), there are 4.34 million African refugees, one-third of
the 13.2 million in the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
