<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Asks for Another 6 Weeks for MONUA's Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan issued on Friday morning his report on the United
Nations Observer Mission in Angola (MONUA), asking the Security
Council to extend MONUA for another short period of up to six
weeks in order to revive the currently stalled peace process in
the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The extension is necessary "to give my Special Representative
(Issa Diallo) an additional opportunity to revive the stalled
peace process" in Angola, he said.
</P>
<P>
The continuation of the Angolan peace process has been
"seriously threatened by negative developments," including the
breaking of all contacts by the Angolan Government with rebel
UNITA, led by Jonas Savimbi, and the government's September 7
recognition of the leadership of the UNITA Renovation Committee,
Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA, the Portuguese acronym for the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola, and its leadership in Bailundo,
central Angola, "bears the primary responsibility for the present
crisis" in the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said in his report that he had asked Diallo to visit
Savimbi to "deliver the strong message of the international
community and to ascertain his intentions concerning the speediest
implementation of the Lusaka Protocol," which was signed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"The (Angolan) Government should facilitate this contact, which
would help to establish UNITA's real intentions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the dialogue between the parties remains elusive and my
Special Representative is unable to maintain meaningful contacts,
and MONUA remains obstructed in its verification activities, I
might have other alternative for the Security Council but to
propose" other actions, he said.
</P>
<P>
The proposed actions include that at the beginning of December,
the United Nations would proceed with the immediate re-adjustment
of its presence throughout the country, with its deployment
concentrated mostly in and around six regional headquarters, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The reconfiguration would be conducted gradually, in order to
fully protect the United Nations personnel and property, and would
be completed by the end of January 1999, he added.
</P>
<P>
MONUA, sent into Angola to monitor the peace process under a
Security Council resolution adopted in June last year, groups 1077
civil and military observers from such countries as Argentina,
Bangladesh, Ghana, Pakistan, Romania, Russia and Spain.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government, which blamed Savimbi for his negative
role in the peace process, had disqualified the UNITA leader for
peace dialogue before recognizing the UNITA Renovation Committee
as the legal partner for peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Angola has long been plunged into civil war since its
independence in 1975.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papandreou: Margins Still Exist for Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Margins still existed for a
political solution to the Kosovo crisis, and activation of the
orders for NATO military intervention in Kosovo could be delayed
until such a solution was found, Greece's Alternate Foreign
Minister George Papandreou said here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on private radio, Papandreou said that Greece firmly
backed the peaceful solution to the Kosovo crisis and was very
reserved on all the scenarios concerning a military intervention
by NATO in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the time limits were narrowing, but Balkan
countries must keep in mind that a military intervention would
also symbolize defeat for them, namely that they could not solve
the problems among themselves.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas also said on Friday
that Athens would not use its right to veto if NATO decided to use
military forces in Kosovo, but Athens would not send troops and
airplanes to take part in any strike.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
stressed that if NATO decided to launch air strike in Kosovo,
Greece would provide no facility other than the activation of NATO
bases in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
