<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt has decided to resume exporting cotton textiles
to European markets as of next week, the Al Ahram reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after the EU foreign ministers early this
week refused to impose dumping taxes on the commodities, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the Textile Industries Chamber Al Motaz Billah
Abdul Maqsoud said the resumption will generally improve the value
of textile exports.
</P>
<P>
He said textile exports have declined by 17 percent over the
past eight months and exports of cloth alone dropped from 185
million Egyptian pounds (53 million U.S. dollars) to 116 million
pounds (34 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has instructed that
all ministries and public sector authorities should first consider
to buy local cars, instead of importing from abroad, for office
use.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak also demanded that unnecessary specifications and terms
not be used as a pretext for imports.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Four natural gas processing plants will be built
under BOT system in Turkey, with a cost of about 3.5 billion
dollars, the Daily News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The four plants will be located respectively in Adapazan,
Gebze, Izmir and Ankara, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The plants in Adapazan, Gebze, Izmir will be built by a
consortium made up of U.S. Intergen company and Turkish Enka firm,
and the fourth one in Ankara will be constructed by the National
Power and Bayindir consortium.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Finance Minister Fuad Sinyoura has voiced
support for privatizing the country's state-run enterprises, the
Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Transferring some public-run services to the private sector
is a positive thing, and could be a lucrative prospect for the
state," he said in an interview with the paper on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The minister suggested that the government could allow several
services to be privatized provided that measures preventing
monopoly were introduced.
</P>
<P>
But he said some sectors such as security and education would
remain under state control
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Bank of Beirut, one of Lebanon's leading banks,
enjoyed a net profit increase in the first nine months of this
year.
</P>
<P>
The balance sheet showed that the bank's net profit in the
first nine months of this year has risen to 9.798 million dollars
from 7.106 million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The bank's interest rates on deposits, loans and commissions
collected from securities were the main sources of profit growth,
the sheet showed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
