<HEADLINE> Greece Decides to Purchase Anti-Aircraft Missile Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Greece decided on Friday to
purchase new small and long range anti-aircraft missile systems as
part of its multi-million dollar five-year armaments program.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made during a meeting of the government
Council of Foreign Affairs and Defense chaired by Greek Prime
Minister Costas Simitis.
</P>
<P>
According to decision, Greece will purchase six long range
"Patriot" missiles from the United States and 21 Russian-made
Thor-M1 systems and 11 French-made Crotale systems. A decision was
also made on the purchase of 45 U.S.-made T6A training aircraft,
10 Canadian-made fire-fighting aircraft and four Navy destroyers.
</P>
<P>
Simitis said after the meeting that the gradual implementation
of the government's armaments program would further increase the
capability and effectiveness of the Greek armed forces and enable
them to directly confront any threat. 
