<HEADLINE> Primakov Satisfied with Talks with EU Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Both Russian Premier Yevgeny
Primakov and visiting Chairman of the European Commission Jacques
Santer are satisfied with the results of their talks held here on
Friday, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said that during the talks "we reiterated the
coincidence of our views on the market-oriented transformations in
Russia."
</P>
<P>
"We both believe that those transformation should lead to the
creation in Russia of a socially-oriented, market-based economy.
Both the European Union and the Russian leaders are of the same
opinion. There are no differences on that issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Primakov, the relations between Russia and the
European Union are developing well, but "ther are major reserves,
which are not being used so far."
</P>
<P>
As for the way out of the current crisis in Russia, Primakov
said ways of reimbursing GKO (state short-term bonds) treasury
bills will be found by late October.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said this applies both to foreign and
domestic holders of GKO treasure bills, the payment of which was
frozen from August 17, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Primakov promised that no more statements like the one of
August 17 will come from the government and the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the program of the new government, Primakov said
that it "pursues the super-task of carrying out the market reforms
in the interests of our society and building a socially-oriented
economy."
</P>
<P>
The European Commission chairman arrived in Moscow on Friday
for a two-day visit.  
</P>
