<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Reactivate Post Code Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian Postal Service
(NIPOST) is reactivating its post code project after delay by
poor funding, the Postmaster-General Taiwo Olukolu said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The official made the remark at a ceremony in capital Abuja
marking the 1998 World Post Day, saying that the completion of
the post code project is essential to accelerate mail processing
and sorting by using modern technologies.
</P>
<P>
He said the minister of communications is already pursuing the
issue with the government for further assistance.
</P>
<P>
Olukolu also disclosed that the NIPOST is going to expand its
electrical mail service to five more cities, including Ibadan,
Ikeja, Aba, Enugu and Benin, in response to the growing
technological development in the communications industry
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Existing E-mail services in Lagos, Port Harcourt, Warri, Jos,
Abuja, Kano, Kaduna and Onisha will be boosted through new
equipment to cope with increasing traffic, he said.
</P>
<P>
"At the completion of this project this year, it will be
possible for subscribers to send their mails through NIPOST,
using their personal computers at the comfort of their homes or
offices," he was quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria as saying.
</P>
<P>
Olukolu promised to improve NIPOST's services, which he said
has declined in quality in recent times due to shortage of fuel
and collapse of infrastructure, particularly the airlines.
</P>
<P>
He added that the government will provide some funds for the
purchase of new motor vehicles and the rehabilitation of broken
down ones. 
</P>
