<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Peaceful Efforts to End Conflicts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 9 (Xinhua) -- China on Friday called
for efforts to end conflicts in Africa by peaceful means and
promote development in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The call came as Shen Guofang, China's deputy permanent
representative to the United Nations, was delivering a speech at
the plenary session of the General Assembly, which opened a debate
on a report by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the causes of
conflicts and the promotion of sustainable development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Recently regional conflicts in Africa have cropped up
frequently that have affected the unity, stability, security and
development of regions and countries concerned and aroused the
concern and attention of the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Without stability in Africa, there will be no global peace.
Without the development of Africa, world prosperity will not be
possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
The conflicts in Africa can be traced back to profound
historical roots and are, at the same time, set in complicated
present reality, he said.
</P>
<P>
"To resolve the conflicts and maintain stability on the
continent is an important and arduous task for the United
Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Shen listed two points which he believes are
crucial in ending conflicts and promoting development in Africa.
</P>
<P>
First, to respect the sovereignty and territorial integrity
of African countries and refrain from interfering in their
internal affairs is "the prerequisite and starting point for
settling African conflicts," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hold that conflicts and disputes should be settled through
peaceful means," he said, adding, "We believe that the United
Nations should increase its input in Africa, play its constructive
role as a coordinator in settling African conflicts, support
regional efforts and provide necessary assistance to African
countries at their legitimate and reasonable request."
</P>
<P>
Secondly, attention should be given to taking steps to help
promote development in Africa, Shen said, adding the African
economy is improving in recent years, but "the overall reality
is still grim.
</P>
<P>
"Despite their efforts in various aspects, African countries
are still facing the danger of being marginalized in the
globalization process," he said, "Africa still has a long distance
to go to achieve its development."
</P>
<P>
"The international community, especially the developed
countries, should carry out in real earnest its commitments with
regards to funds, debt, market and goods, and create a sound and
development-friendly external environment for Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shen voiced his support for proposals in Annan's
report for reducing the debt burden of African countries,
opening markets wider for African nations and helping Africa
strengthen regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that organizations concerned will, on the basis of a
good understanding and knowledge of Africa, work out a feasible
and specific program that suits the national conditions in African
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Sino-African relations, Shen said that "China has always
cherished its traditional friendship with the African people."
</P>
<P>
"China attaches great importance to strengthening its
cooperation with Africa in various fields. We have always
supported African countries in their efforts to resolve
conflicts and instill lasting peace and respected the African
countries' choice of political system and path of development as
they see fit for their national conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will strive to contribute even more to Africa's development
by continuing to support the efforts of African countries to
develop their national economy and continuing to offer our
assistance within our capacity without attaching any political
conditions," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
