<HEADLINE> Yemen Accepts Arbitration on Dispute with Eritrea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANAA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah
Saleh Friday welcomed the international arbitration of his
country's disputed island of Greater Hanish with Eritrea and pledged
to settle differences with neighbors through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Calling the arbitration "a fair result," Saleh said peaceful
settlement of disputes and differences could help strengthen peace
and security in the region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the London-based International Arbitration
Committee has reached a unanimous resolution in favor of Yemen's
sovereignty over the disputed island in the south of the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said his country is satisfied with, and accepts "the fair
result of the arbitration."
</P>
<P>
The Greater Hanish has an area of 90 square kilometers and is
28 nautical miles off the Yemeni coast and 32 nautical miles off
the Eritrean coast. Armed clashes erupted between Yemen and
Eritrea on December 15, 1995.
</P>
<P>
The two countries agreed to settle the dispute peacefully
through international arbitration on May 21, 1996. 
</P>
