<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany, U.S. Agree to Authorize NATO Action in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor-elect
Gerhard Schroeder told U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday he
concurs in the authorization of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) plans for military action in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's commitment was one step away from authorizing an
attack, but Schroeder also warned Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic not to count on Germany refusing to act against him.
</P>
<P>
"If the Yugoslav president thinks he can depend on doubting the
German position and readiness to act together with the
international community, he's making a big mistake," said
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Schroeder spoke with reporters in the Rose Garden
as the president escorted his guest from the Oval Office to lunch
in the private residential area of the White House.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing German Chancellor Helmut Kohl has said Germany will
provide 14 fighter jets and 500 soldiers for use in a NATO force,
but parliamentary approval will be needed to deploy them.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said he expected the current German government to
announce its decision on the matter on Monday. Schroeder takes
over at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
"(Milosevic) must fulfil the U.N. resolutions completely and we
will do all we can to ensure it is fulfilled. The U.S. knows that
is our view," Shroeder said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who has been arguing in favor of military strikes for
days, said Milosevic still had not complied with demands of a U.N.
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, approved on September 23, requires Belgrade to
end the violence, withdraw forces, let tens of thousands of
refugees return home, give humanitarian relief organizations
access to people who need them, and begin negotiations with Kosovo
Albanians on autonomy for their region.
</P>
<P>
"The first issue is whether Germany will support NATO issuing
the action order to make sure that the plans are in place and
authorized if NATO action should be need," said Clinton. "That is
what he (Schroeder) said 'yes' to today."
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced it is important that we authorize NATO to act.
That's where the agreement is," added Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the White House meeting, Joschka Fischer, who is
in line to be Germany's foreign minister, said full authorization
from Germany for action in Kosovo could not come until Schroeder's
new government is in place.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in office now," said Fischer. "After October 27 we
will be in government and the new majority will be capable" of
acting.
</P>
<P>
"We agree with the positions of the Western alliance that there
must be a serious pressure on Slobodan Milosevic," added Fischer.
</P>
<P>
"In this transition situation, the Americans have to understand
that our possibilities for action are very limited," he said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder arrived here late on Thursday. Earlier, Schroeder
discussed the global economic crisis with World Bank President
James Wolfensohn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
