<HEADLINE> U.S. Cotton and Soybean Productions Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. cotton production
fell 2 percent this month, due partly to poor weather conditions,
the Agriculture Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's cotton-growing regions such as Georgia's cotton
production dropped 50,000 bales from last month and Texas'
harvested acres declined 250,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
The hot and dry weather also took a toll on soybean production
but not enough to affect prices, which rebounded slightly.
Soybeans are forecast at a record 2.77 billion bushels, but
production is down 5 percent from September projection.
</P>
<P>
Soybean prices could be propped up further by a the fact that
worldwide production is off 2.5 million metric tons from earlier
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Corn, forecast at 9.74 billion bushels, remained unchanged from
last month. Corn production is still up 4 percent from last year.
If realized, this would be the second-largest production and the
second-highest yield on record, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Officials are also predicting a drop in this year's orange
crop. The initial forecast for this year is 11 million tons, down
21 percent from last year's record 13.9 million tons. Florida's
orange forecast is 190 million boxes, about 22 percent less than
the record 244 million boxes produced last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
