<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Rally With Firmer Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- European share prices staged a
recovery Friday after the dollar strengthened overnight against
European currencies, and more European central banks cut their
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday there had been sharp falls in equities after the
dollar had fallen sharply amid persistent fears for the growth
prospects of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
London shares ended the week on a positive note, buoyed by a
recovery in U.S. stocks in late trading and an encouraging cut in
interest rates by Ireland and Portugal. Ireland lowered base rates
by 1 percent to 5.75 percent, while Portugal followed Spain with a
0.5 percent cut to 4 percent. Italy had also been expected to
follow suit, but the move was delayed when the government fell.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE index rose 124.5 points to 4,823.4, reversing most of
Thursday's steep falls.
</P>
<P>
However, traders said that global stock markets continue to
swing up and down, and that no gains are guaranteed to last for
long.
</P>
<P>
One factor helping sentiment Friday was the panic selling of
government bonds, which was apparently linked to hedge funds
unwinding their positions. This made stocks relatively more
attractive.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong related stocks did well on the back of the sharp
recovery in the Hang Seng index.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Dax 30 index recovered by more than 3 percent
to 3,983, up 87 points.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the bourse recovered from its Thursday plunge, too,
putting in one of the best performances in Europe in thin trading.
The Cac 40 index was up by 132 points to 3,092. 
</P>
</TEXT>
