<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Reported to Take Measures against PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's semi-official Anatolia
News Agency Friday reported that Syria has promised to take
measures to rein in Turkey's Kurdish rebels on its territory.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified diplomatic sources, the agency said the
pledge was contained in an oral massage from Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad to his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel,
conveyed by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi who was on a
mediation mission.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering its rebel group
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) and threatened to use force against
rebel camps inside Syria. Syria denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that there are PKK sympathizers among the
people. So, we can not stop the PKK activities immediately, but we
banned the PKK organization and we are arresting the PKK
militants," Assad was quoted as saying in the oral message.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Assad acknowledged that there were PKK
members in Syria and affirmed that he did not support them.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi arrived here Friday morning to convey written and oral
messages from Iranian President Mohammad Khatami to Demirel. He
held talks with Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem on the crisis
between Ankara and Damascus, in an effort to mediate a peaceful
settlement of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for autonomy of the
Kurdish minority in southeastern Turkey. Ankara has vowed to wipe
out the rebels at whatever cost.
</P>
<P>
Syria has criticized Turkey for forming a military alliance
with Israel that threatens Arab security and undermines its
bargaining positions in negotiations with the Jewish sate.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has massed heavy forces along Syrian borders late last
week and issued an ultimatum this week, threatening to uproot PKK
bases in Syria by force if Damascus fails to stop supporting the
PKK within 45 days.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Kharrazi were exerting
efforts to try to ease the mounting tensions between the two
neighbors and attain a peaceful solution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
