<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Kosovo Air Strikes Worries Relief Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Relief organizations working
in the Serbian province of Kosovo said on Friday the threat of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) air strikes had
disrupted their work at a critical time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference in Washington, officials from
five relief agencies said the important thing was to act fast so
that international staff can go back to Kosovo and resume
humanitarian work.
</P>
<P>
They said their main worry was that NATO attacks would turn the
Serbian minority in Kosovo against their staff, without
necessarily convincing displaced Albanians that it is safe for
them to return to their villages.
</P>
<P>
Joelle Tanguy, who works for Medecins sans Frontieres, said it
would be naive to belief that a Tomahawk cruise missile could
solve the problems of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Martone said that air strikes by NATO, which could take place
within less than a week, may well prove counterproductive in the
search for a political solution.
</P>
<P>
"Serbia being somewhat of a pariah state, force emboldens the
hardline position. It furthers people's sense of isolation and
exclusion and victimization by foreigners," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It certainly could interrupt the leverage you might have for
negotiations, if the relationship is one of overwhelming force, as
in this case," he added
</P>
<P>
"Our staff say that perhaps air strikes without a troop
enforcement would not help them. The fact that their own safety is
in jeopardy and many of the staff have evacuated impedes our
ability to provide assistance at a critical time," said Gerald
Martone of the International Rescue Committee.
</P>
<P>
"Our mandate is to save lives and to help those who are
suffering. If there are air strikes, there will be casualties,
people will die and this is not something we are in favor of,"
added Serge Duss of the Christian group World Vision.
</P>
<P>
However, he added: "We understand that when political solutions
are sought, sometimes military action has to take place.".
</P>
<P>
Only Catholic Relief Services said it had decided to have them
stay for the moment but spokesman Phil Oldham said the
organization was reviewing that decision every day.
</P>
<P>
Oldham said the staff had already seen signs of hostility from
local Serbs in Kosovo, who see the relief workers as
representatives of a hostile force.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. asked Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to end the
fighting in Kosovo, withdraw troops and begin negotiations with
ethnic Albanians for a final settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
