<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hubble Detects Most Distant Galaxies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Hubble Space Telescope
has detected galaxies of stars more than 12 billion light-years
away, The Washington Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rodger I. Thompson, an astronomer from the University of
Arizona, and his team focused an infrared instrument on the
Telescope on a narrow patch of space and detected about 100
galaxies never before seen, and 10 of them were at extreme
distance.
</P>
<P>
Thompson said that the galaxies are seen as they were when the
universe was only about 5 percent of its present age.
</P>
<P>
Astronomers generally think the universe began with the "big
bang" about 13 billion years ago. Since then, the galaxies have
been moving rapidly away from each other, spreading out and
becoming more distant. For this reason, distance and time can be
measured together. Light from the distant objects traveled for
about 12 billion years before being detected by Hubble.
</P>
<P>
A light-year equals about 6 trillion miles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Calls for End to Nigeria Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Some government ministers from
the Commonwealth Friday recommended that member states start
lifting sanctions against Nigeria as the African country is trying
to restore democracy.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of the eight-nation Commonwealth Ministerial
Action Group (CMAG) in London, the ministers said in a statement
that the meeting marked an important step towards the
normalization of relations between Nigeria and the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
"In recognition of the progress made by Nigeria so far towards
the restoration of democratic government, (we) recommend that
member states begin forthwith to lift sanctions in existence
against Nigeria," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
CMAG chairman Stan Mudenge told a news conference, "We believe
that the integrity and the nature of the transition program
compels us to give (Nigerians) further encouragement so that they
continue along the lines they have so far adopted."
</P>
<P>
"We want to make it loud and clear to the Nigerian government
and people that they should continue along the correct path they
have now chosen," said Mudenge, who is the foreign minister of
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
However, there should be no discussion of whether to lift
Nigeria's suspension from the 54-nation body until presidential
elections set for February 27.
</P>
<P>
The CMAG comprises Britain, Canada, New Zealand, Botswana,
Barbados, Malaysia, Zimbabwe and Ghana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
