<HEADLINE> Iran Says to Consider Proposals by an Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said Friday that the proposals raised
by Seyed Jalal, a well-known Afghan residing in Saudi Arabia, were
"considerable."
</P>
<P>
He said the proposals were worthy to be discussed on the
condition that the Taliban will release all held Iranians, return
the remaining bodies of the killed Iranian diplomats, bring to
justice those responsible for the killings and apologize for the
slayings, the Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban has refused the Iranian demands.
</P>
<P>
Tehran radio did not give details about Jalal and his
proposals. Jalal helped secure the release Friday of five Iranian
businessmen, who were captured by the Taliban 15 months ago in
western Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi also expressed welcome to initiatives for the release
of captured Iranians in Afghanistan, hoping them will return home
soon.
</P>
<P>
Tensions between Iran and Afghan Taliban militia have been on
rising since August after Iran accused Taliban of capturing scores
of Iranians, including nine diplomats and a journalist, when it
took over the northern Afghan city of Mazar-e-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Iran massed heavy troops along its borders with Afghanistan for
military exercises, with an apparent aim to show force, after the
Taliban admitted that its men killed seven of the missing
diplomats and the journalist.
</P>
<P>
There were reports on Thursday of skirmishes between Iranian
border guards and Taliban fighters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jalal has told Tehran radio that the Taliban
proposed to send a joint delegation, made up of representatives
from Iran, the Taliban, the Organization of the Islamic Conference
and the United Nations to Mazar-e-Sharif to probe the killing.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that over 30 Iranian nationals were still in the
hand of the Taliban, which accused Iran of supporting its rivals
in northern Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
