<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OECD E-Commerce Meeting Ends in Ottawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ministers of the Organization for
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) ended their two-day
meeting on electronic commerce here today, without much concrete
to show back at home.
</P>
<P>
"Elements of a 'shared vision' for global electronic commerce
emerged from the conference," said an OECD news release issued at
the end of the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The ministers discussed electronic commerce in the context of
four broad themes: building trust, establishing marketplace rules,
enhancing the information infrastructure and maximizing the
benefits.
</P>
<P>
And they adopted an action plan that set the course for future
work in such areas as consumer protection, privacy, authentication
and taxation, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
"Each country will continue to pursue its domestic policy
independently in these areas," declared John Manley, chair of the
conference and Canada's minister of industry.
</P>
<P>
"What we have achieved here is agreement on the kinds of global
issues that policy makers should keep in mind when creating
electronic commerce initiatives in their respective countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of consumer protection, the ministers agreed to
work together to ensure that consumer are afforded a transparent
and effective level of protection. A guideline for consumer
protection will be drafted within 1999.
</P>
<P>
As to the much-contested issue of privacy, it was agreed that
OECD, in cooperation with industry and business, should provide
practical guidance on the implementation of its privacy guidelines
based on national experiences and examples.
</P>
<P>
On taxation, the ministers agreed that taxation principles
which guide governments in relations to conventional commerce
should also guide them in relation to electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
There was also agreement that consumption taxes should be
levied in the country where consumption takes place, and that for
the purpose of these taxes the supply of digitized products should
be treated as a supply of goods, the OECD release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Govt to Free 10,000 Genocide Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
planned to free about 10,000 genocide suspects, the Rwanda News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by Minister of Justice Faustin
Nteziryayo Thursday night at the end of a one-day meeting in
Kigali, capital of Rwanda, which was attended by the minister,
prosecutors in the country and representatives of the Ministry of
Interior, and the Ministry of Defense.
</P>
<P>
Nteziryayo explained that most of the 10,000 suspects to be
released are people detained without sufficient charges, or those
whose files are incomplete.
</P>
<P>
"Rwanda abides by the rule of law. It is ununderstandable
that someone is kept in prison for four years without any file,"
Nteziryayo said, adding that those who will be released will be
sent back to their communes.
</P>
<P>
The 10,000 people will join about 1,500 others who were set
free for different reasons ranging from old age, terminal
illness, to lack of enough evidence against them.
</P>
<P>
It was explained that the decision was first adopted during a
consultative meeting attended by President Pasteur Bizimungu,
cabinet ministers, governors, representatives of political
parties on August 4.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was aimed at streamlining the domestic and
external politics of the country, as well as discussing
mechanisms for solving current crucial problems.
</P>
<P>
After a year and a half of trials in the country's criminal
courts, only a small portion of the genocide suspects, about 400,
have been judged, of which over 120 were sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
The first 22 genocide criminals were executed in public on
April 25 this year in five different locations of the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
