<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov warned Saturday that the use of force by NATO in Kosovo
could lead to the revision of relations between Russia and the
alliance.
</P>
<P>
Primakov reiterated Moscow's resolve to veto any U.N.
resolution authorizing NATO strikes.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot allow this resolution," the Interfax news agency
quoted Primakov as saying.
</P>
<P>
If NATO goes ahead with the threatened air strikes in Kosovo
by passing the U.N. Security Council, the whole system of
international security will be eroded, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
That would mean that such actions unsanctioned by the Security
Council are possible against other countries, too, he said.
</P>
<P>
He quoted Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov as saying that
"there are no clear signs that the situation is getting worse."
</P>
<P>
Ivanov has just returned from Belgrade, where he met with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, and from London, where he
attended a session of the Contact Group on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Primakov expressed the hope that the problem will be solved by
political means. 
