<HEADLINE> China Develops Super Hybrid Rice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China will grow super
high-yield hybrid rice within the next 3-5 years, according to
experts attending a scientific investigation meeting today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in Changsha, capital of central China's
Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing research project, funded at a cost of 10 million
yuan, will eventually raise the daily hybrid rice production to
between 90-100 kg per hectare. The quality of the new variety will
equal the quality of existing second grade rice in terms of
resistance to pests, according to Yuan Longping, China's
well-known "Father of Hybrid Rice."
</P>
<P>
Improving the cultivation of high-yield rice has been a global
priority in recent years. China plans to cultivate new rice
strains with annual per hectare output of 9,000 kg-10,500 kg by
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Yuan, a member of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, has
conducted extensive research related to the cultivation of new
strains of hybrid rice. Yuan developed and introduced new
techniques for cultivating hybrid rice in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
