<HEADLINE> Iran's Group Offers New Award for Rushdie's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian student organization
has announced a new award for carrying out the death sentence on
British writer Salman Rushdie, the evening daily Kayhan reported
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Hezbollah Students Association announced the award of one
billion rials (about 333,000 U.S. dollars) in a statement to
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi to protest the
government's promise not to carry out the death sentence on
Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
Kayhan said that the members of the central committee of
the association delivered the statement to an official of the
Foreign Ministry. However, it did not mention when the statement
was handed over.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed regret that Kharrazi promised to his
British counterpart Robin Cook last month in New York that
the Iranian government would not take or support any action to
threaten the life of Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
Iran's late supreme leader Ayatollah Musavi Khomeini issued a
religious decree or fatwa in 1989 to sentence Rushdie to death
for his controversial book the Satanic Verses.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Khordad 15 Foundation later announced an award of 2.5
million dollars to carry out Khomeini's fatwa against Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
On September 24, Kharrazi announced at a joint press
conference with Cook that the Iranian government has nothing to
do with the award and will not support it.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi and Cook also announced jointly to upgrade the
diplomatic relations between the two countries to the
ambassadorial level by putting aside the Rushdie issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian student association urged the Iranian Foreign
Ministry to at least support the implementation of Khomeini's
fatwa and to apologize to the Iranian nation for giving
promise to Britain over the issue.
</P>
<P>
It stressed that only the Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei can make any comments on Khomeini's fatwa, but so
far Khamenei did not show any retreat from the stance on how
to carry out the death sentence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
