<HEADLINE> Quebec Expected to Have Tight Election Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada's French-speaking
province of Quebec could have a very tight election race if the
ruling Party Quebecois (PQ) chooses to call an election this fall,
according to a poll released Saturday.
</P>
<P>
While Quebec's opposition Liberal Party still leads the PQ by
about four percentage points, the poll also shows a high level of
satisfaction with the PQ government despite years of cuts in
spending on health care and social services.
</P>
<P>
Among decided Quebec voters, 48.7 percent said they would opt
for the Liberals, while 44.9 percent preferred the PQ.
</P>
<P>
These numbers have changed little over the past six months.
Support for the Liberals has dropped slightly, and the PQ has
gained marginally, Canada's main newspaper, the Globe and Mail,
reported.
</P>
<P>
But among the key Francophone voters, 53.8 percent said they
would choose the PQ, compared with 39.4 percent for the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 percent of the voters in Quebec are French
speakers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 53.8 percent said they were satisfied or very
satisfied with the government, compared with 35.5 percent who said
they were dissatisfied or very dissatisfied.
</P>
<P>
The poll, conducted from Monday to Thursday this week by Groupe
Leger &AMP; Leger, questioned 1,070 people over the age of 18, and had
a margin error of 3.1 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Quebec Premier Lucien Bouchard said Friday that he would tell
voters next week whether they would be going to the polls this
fall.
</P>
<P>
If he decides to call an election, the possible dates would be
November 23 or 30, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
