<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Why Zimbabwean Currency Devalues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean Dollar, once a
stable currency, has devalued to present 33 Dollars against one
U.S. Dollar from 18 dollars against one U.S. Dollar at the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of September, the Zimbabwean Dollar dropped to a
historical low with 39 Dollars against one U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predict that the value of the currency in the south
African country will further tumble to 50 dollars against one
U.S. Dollar by the end of this year. The drastic devaluation is
feared to be another factor threatening the country's already
poor economy.
</P>
<P>
The sharp fall of the Zimbabwean Dollar began on November 14
last year, when it took a heavy plunge losing 75 percent of its
value against the U.S. Dollar.
</P>
<P>
Since "the black Friday", the local currency has been
swinging, reaching new lows and firming marginally on the back of
the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Thus the average consumer price has so far risen by about 50
percent compared with that at the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The lack of substantial efforts to reduce imports to offset
the reduced export earnings has been regarded by experts as one
of the reasons for the currency devaluation.
</P>
<P>
The decrease of export revenue from tobacco and mining
industries, two biggest foreign exchange earners of the country,
is taken as yet another cause for the currency's value slip.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Herbert Murewa has estimated that due to the
falls his country's foreign exchange earnings will drop by nine
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Taking advantage of the devaluation of Rand, the South African
currency, businessmen in Zimbabwe have spent large amounts of
foreign currencies on importing large quantities of merchandise
from South Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank was unable to inject enough foreign
currencies on the market to meet the demand, which resulted in
the loosing of confidence by domestic and foreign investors in
the prospects of Zimbabuwe's economy.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, sending troops to the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) to back President Laurent Kabila has also strained
Zimbabwe's already meager foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the country has increased its monetary supply
this year by over 30 percent, exceeding the planned 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
To contain the slumping of the currency and curb outflow of
foreign exchanges, the central bank has raised its rediscount
rate three times in the past 10 months to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government has also increased import duties by 100 percent
and increased statutory reserves for commercial banks and
merchant banks from 20 percent to 25 percent and from four
percent to five percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
But economists in Zimbabwe said the measures are short-term
and appealed to the government to map out long-term polices to
introduce export incentives.
</P>
<P>
Increasing import duties without stimulating exports is half
baked measure, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Observer Claims Kosovo Crisis Exaggerated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A European Union (EU) observer
in Kosovo said Friday that the crisis there had been intentionally
exaggerated by the United States, a Finnish newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Finnish EU observer Pentti Metso told Helsingin Sanomat in
a telephone interview that the exaggeration was designed to rally
support for a proposed U.S.-led NATO air strike against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In fact, said Metso, who has been an observer for three months,
the tension in Kosovo had obviously relaxed this week and EU
observers had no report of new conflicts between the Serb forces
and the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Metso complained the EU observers' claims on the
Kosovo situation had been "put aside", adding that the U.S. envoy
to Yugoslavia met only with U.S. observers for information.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that, among the total of 22 observers, Americans
and Russians were the majority and based themselves in the Kosovo
capital of Pristina. Four EU observers were scattered the province.
</P>
<P>
So far, only the four EU observers continued their work while
the others had left Kosovo in case of possible NATO military
strikes.
</P>
<P>
"Since all the rescue organizations have fled Kosovo, possible
NATO military strikes will harm at least the refugees there,"
Metso noted.
</P>
<P>
The most important thing was to help all parties involved in
the crisis keep in contact and negotiation, the Finnish observer
believed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
