<HEADLINE> Russian PM Against Early Presidential Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said Saturday that he is "categorically against early
presidential elections".
</P>
<P>
"Early presidential elections can result in a situation which
will not facilitate stabilization in society," Primakov told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, it will lead to a division and whip up
political passions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov's statement came two days after Gennady Seleznyov,
speaker of the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, called
for a national referendum on confidence in President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
During a day of national protest Wednesday, many demanded the
ouster of Yeltsin, whose current term expires in 2000, in addition
to repayment of back wages and pensions.
</P>
<P>
"After this large-scale action of protest ... it would be more
legitimate to call a referendum in Russia on whether society
trusts or does not trust the president, on whether the president
should or should not resign," Seleznyov said.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin expressed "regret" over Seleznyov's statement and
indicated he would serve out his term until 2000, presidential
spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin said.
</P>
<P>
Russia is grappling with its worst financial and economic
crisis since 1991, with the ruble shedding 60 percent against the
dollar since the August 17 decision by the government of Sergei
Kiriyenko to effectively devalue the national currency and default
on some foreign and domestic debts.
</P>
<P>
The current government under Primakov, who took office a month
ago, is hard pressed to find ways to stabilize the situation and
mitigate social discontent.
</P>
<P>
An early presidential election "will create a situation in
which it will be hard to overcome the complex situation in which
we are now," the Itar-Tass news agency quoted Primakov as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
