<HEADLINE> Indonesian Founding President's Daughter Re-elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Megawati Soekarnoputri,
daughter of Indonesia's founding president Soekarno, was
re-elected on Saturday as general chairwoman of her faction of the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) for 1998-2003 at its congress in
Denpasar, Bali.
</P>
<P>
According to Antara News Agency, the congress also gave a full
mandate to Megawati to appoint others to sit in the party's
central executive committee under her leadership for the next five
years.
</P>
<P>
After Megawati's re-election, the congress was adjourned to
give her time to draw up the party's super structure and decide
who would fill the positions in it.
</P>
<P>
The conflict-ridden PDI is the second largest opposition party
in Indonesia. Megawati was for the first time appointed chairwoman
of the PDI at a national congress in Surabaya, East Java, 1993.
She was ousted two years ago as leader of the PDI in a move backed
by the Soeharto government.
</P>
<P>
Megawati has been demanding that she be reinstated as leader of
the PDI.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, who replaced the late Soekarno in 1965, was himself
forced out of office on May 21 this year in a wave of public anger
and bloody riots amid the Asian economic crisis which plunged
Indonesia into its worst recession in decades.
</P>
<P>
The government-backed PDI held its congress in Palu, Central
Sulawesi, in August, and elected Budi Hardjono as new chairman of
the party. 
</P>
