<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: Kosovo Crisis Cannot Be Bombed Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- With the Kosovo crisis becoming
increasingly intense and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana
beginning the countdown for military strikes against Yugoslavia,
fair-minded world opinion is calling on the leaders of NATO and
Western countries to abandon military plans and to continue
seeking an effective and peaceful settlement.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo issue is complicated by both historical and
contemporary factors. But in the final analysis, it is
Yugoslavia's internal affair which should be tackled by the
Yugoslav people themselves.
</P>
<P>
However, some Western countries are threatening to unleash
military strikes against Yugoslavia and are racking their brains
for excuses for their proposed actions. The move, an intervention
in the internal affairs of a sovereign state, not only obviously
violates the United Nations Charter and the commonly-recognized
norms of international law, but also runs counter to the trend of
the times, which calls for peace and development.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the world community has expressed deep concern over
the cloud of war hanging over Kosovo. Some NATO member states
also have reservations over military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the Yugoslav federal government, hoping to
demonstrate its determination to find a political solution, has
formed an interim executive council for Kosovo's autonomy, which
consists of representatives from all Kosovo ethnic groups,
including ethnic Albanians, thus granting Kosovo the status of an
autonomous province. A series of measures were also taken to
stablize the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Currently, large-scale armed conflicts have ceased in Kosovo,
and the overall situation is moving towards relaxation. Under
such circumstances, NATO military attacks, instead of creating
peace, are sure to encounter firm resistance from the Yugoslav
Federation, causing the war to spread and the conflict to
escalate. It will also complicate the crisis and pose a new
threat to peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Today, the international community is mediating a political
solution to the crisis. Meanwhile, people hope the Yugoslav
Federation will comply with relevant U.N. Security Council
resolution, cooperate actively with international community,
attach more importance to humanitarian factors and take
substantial steps for constructive cooperation, thus gradually
eliminating tensions among ethnic groups in Kosovo, and creating
more favorable conditions for resolving the crisis through
dialogue rather than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The former Yugoslav region was once a so-called "powder keg"
that ignited the First World War. In post-Cold War years, people
there continued suffering from civil wars. Historical experience
proves that bombs cannot disperse crises in the region. Instead,
they will worsen the situation and result in unforeseeable serious
consequences. To resort to political dialogue while respecting
Yugoslavia's sovereignty and maintaining its territorial
integrity, is the only way to tackle the Kosovo crisis once and
for all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
