<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Priority Placed on Post-flood Epidemic Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Vice Premier Li Lanqing on
Friday urged areas recovering from heavy summer flooding to launch
a massive clean-up and disease control campaign to prevent
outbreaks of epidemics.
</P>
<P>
Local branches of the National Committee for Patriotic Public
Health Campaign (NCPPHC) will direct related work scheduled
through next spring, according to Li, a member of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign is extremely urgent to overcome heavy damage to
both the living and working environments, and eliminate the
possibility of epidemics early next spring," Li, who serves
concurrently as director of the NCPPHC, said at a televised
national meeting Friday.
</P>
<P>
China's patriotic public health campaign, which mobilizes urban
and rural residents to respond to natural disaster and eradicate
pest infestations, has a history dating back well over 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"Government and Party officials at all levels should place top
priority on the campaign, with special emphasis on epidemic
control," said Li said, adding that the State Council has
coordinated related departments and arranged for needed funds and
materials.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed that work should center on rural areas, hygiene and
the eradication of pests such as rats, flies and mosquitos.
</P>
<P>
He urged local departments to ensure supplies of potable water
and uncontaminated food in order to prevent intestinal diseases
and food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
Planning and financial departments should join the NCPPHC in
providing financial support, and departments of civil affairs
should allocate a portion of donated funds and materials to
support disease control efforts, according to Li. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
