<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Resumes Food Aid to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) said Saturday it has delivered 1,244 tons of food to over
100,000 people in Upper Nile State of Sudan after food aid was
suspended in July for security reason.
</P>
<P>
The food was delivered by a WFP three-river-barge convoy to 40
locations within the basin of the Sobat River earlier this month
for the so-called "hunger gap" season, WFP said in a press
release reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The famine victims there are agro-pastoralists of the Nuer
ethnic group whose main crops include sorghum and maize.
</P>
<P>
The convoy is due to arrive at Nyandit near the
Sudanese-Ethiopian border at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
WFP said people living in the Sobat corridor receive food aid
by barge only between May and November last year when river
levels are high enough to allow passage of the barge convoy.
</P>
<P>
WFP, the U.N. front-line agency in the fight against global
hunger, has delivered over 87,000 tons of food to more than one
million hungry Sudanese since the first barge convoy was mounted
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The food has been delivered along 2,500 kilometers of
waterways along four rivers: the Nile, Sobat, Bahr el Ghazal and
Zeraf.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Sudan has dragged into its 15 years between
the Moslem-led government and the Sudan People's Liberation Army
fighting for more autonomy and religion freedom in the Animist
and Christian-dominated south.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
