<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hours or Days Before Kosovo Strike Action: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A NATO official said on
Saturday that the allies were just hours or days away from air
strikes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said after
Saturday's extraordinary North Atlantic Council meeting that the
whole situation had reached a critical point where NATO had
cleared all the way for the final activation order.
</P>
<P>
"The allies are moving imminently toward a decision (for
activation)," said the official, who added that all technical
preparation for the limited air strike and the ensuing air
campaign had been completed.
</P>
<P>
The NATO ambassadors were briefed "in great detail" during the
council meeting on air strikes and the air campaign to be mounted
by the allies should Belgrade fail again to comply fully with the
demands of the international community.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to a decisive phase where Slobodan Milosevic
(Yugoslav president) can still avoid the NATO attack by complying
with the international community at the eleventh hour," said the
official.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's meeting of the North Atlantic Council, the
decision-making body of the 16-nation alliance, was expected to
arrive at the issuance of the activation order, or ACTOR in NATO
jargon.
</P>
<P>
But the absence of domestic approval in a couple of NATO member
states seemed to have stopped the meeting short of issuing the
order which does not necessarily lead to immediate attack.
</P>
<P>
Germany, Italy, Greece and Portugal were said to be still in
the process of domestic approval though some doubt that it would
take longer than what the NATO official had predicted to complete,
especially in Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Germany still needs approval from the new government while
Italy may have to wait for its new government to take care of the
matter.
</P>
<P>
The allies have already started to enhance the safety of the
NATO-led SFOR troops in Bosnia as threats had been made to take
revenge on the peacekeepers should NATO go ahead with air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Britain and Australia reportedly started
evacuating non-essential embassy staff and the families of
diplomats from Belgrade for fear that they would be taken hostage
once air strikes were underway as was the case in 1994 when NATO
missiles hit Serbian targets in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
NATO has amassed a total of 340 warplanes including 260 from
the United States which also provided two B2 Stealth bombers and
six B52 bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
