<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Still Waiting for Approval From Some Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Although NATO has threatened
to air strike to force Belgrade into full compliance, it failed to
activate the last order due to the absence of domestic approval in
some member states.
</P>
<P>
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana told the press after
Saturday's meeting of the North Atlantic Council, the
decision-making body of the 16-nation alliance, that the allies
had cleared all the way for the issuance of the final order of
activation, or ACTOR in NATO jargon.
</P>
<P>
The NATO chief said Belgrade had still not complied with the
United Nations Security Council Resolution 1199 calling for a at
this point, three weeks after its adoption. The resolution calls
for a ceasefire in Kosovo and an entry of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The NATO ambassadors overviewed a detailed analysis from the
NATO Military Committee and evaluated the situation on the ground
in Kosovo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Solana said that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had
better comply with the demands of the international community or
face imminent NATO action.
</P>
<P>
When asked why NATO did not take the decision to activate the
air strike during the day's council meeting, Solana explained that
NATO wanted to continue the diplomatic pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
But the inability to issue the activation order seemed to have
arisen from the absence of domestic approval from some NATO member
states.
</P>
<P>
Germany now has to re-evaluate the approval given by the
outgoing Chancellor Helmut Kohl while Italian Prime Minister
Romano Prodi just lost a confidence vote by a single vote and is
now serving as the caretaker of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Portugal were said to yet complete their respective
approval processes.
</P>
<P>
NATO needs a consensus from all member states before taking any
decision on actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
