<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia President Urges Press to Improve Professional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie Saturday called on the country's press to improve the
professional standards of journalists, saying it was a must in the
current reform era.
</P>
<P>
"The standards, of course, must be set by the press itself, not
by the government or by any other party. Because those who are
most familiar about such standards are the mass media chiefs," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Opening the 20th Congress of the Indonesian Journalists
Association (PWI) in Semarang, capital of Central Java province,
Habibie urged the media people to respect and implement the press
code of ethics and uphold moral and legal norms.
</P>
<P>
The press must be trustworthy, fair, balanced and avoid
prejudices, the president was quoted by Antara News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"The government is now preparing a new basic press law which is
in line with the spirit of reform. God willing, the bill will be
finished in the near future," the president said.
</P>
<P>
The government would not interfere with the press
organizations' policies on news reporting, he said, adding that
the decision to publish or not to publish any news item is
entirely for the press itself to make.
</P>
<P>
He also said freedom brings certain responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
A free press must realize that news may have a positive but
also a negative impact on the people, and therefore they must be
responsible for the stories they publish, he said.
</P>
<P>
The press should be responsible not to the government but to
the whole nation, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the association will elect its next
general chairman and secretary general. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
