<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Security Remains Vital to Elderly Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A recent national survey
revealed that elderly Chinese still regard the family an
indispensable aspect of life, financial supports and spiritual
sustenance.
</P>
<P>
Some 98 percent of 120 million elderly Chinese over the age of
60 continue to enjoy various degrees of family life, with only one
percent living in social welfare centers or homes for senior
citizens, according to the survey conducted by the China Research
Center on Aging.
</P>
<P>
Senior citizens spend 77 percent of time in various pursuits
such as caring for younger members of their families, doing
household chores and exercising. The remaining time involved
either jobs or social activities.
</P>
<P>
From a financial standpoint, the survey revealed that various
forms of support from children account for the bulk of income for
elderly people.
</P>
<P>
However, it also revealed that 60 percent of elderly people in
urban areas and and five percent in rural areas receive
pensions. The survey also revealed that 60 percent of elderly
parents living alone receive support from their children.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 percent of elderly respondents indicated they
would prefer to live with their children and grandchildren, and
would only express their innermost thoughts and feelings to their
spouses and children.
</P>
<P>
Elderly parents and children living apart is quite common in
today's China. Nonetheless, studies point to the limited effects
separation has on family ties.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of children and elderly parents live in
the same city or town, with some 85 percent seeing each other at
least once a week, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
"The family will continue to play an extremely important role
in providing for the elderly, especially at a time when China is
experiencing a rapidly growing aging population which will reach
400 million by the year 2050," according to center deputy director
Xiao Zhenyu.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Container Producer Leads World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The China International Ocean
Shipping Container Group (CIOSC) has emerged as the world's major
producer in its sector with total sales of containers rated at one
million TEUs (twenty-foot equivalent units).
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen-based CIOSC, founded in 1982, has exported 100 percent
of its output in spite of the financial turmoil sweeping Southeast
Asia, and has remained its growth momentum, with total output
and sales for the first nine months of this year exceeding last
year's total.
</P>
<P>
Some 90 percent of the company's total output has been
produced since 1994.
</P>
<P>
CIOSC's long-term customers include the vast majority of the
world's leading container leasing and shipping companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
