<HEADLINE> Winners of Ten HK Outstanding Youngsters Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's ace male singer
Cheung Hok Yau is among the six local people who have won this
year's Ten Outstanding Young People (TOYP) Selection awards, it
was announced at a press conference here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Being named as one of the six winners of the Ten Outstanding
Young Poeple awards, I feel like being as young as others. And I
will continue to do what I think obligatory and worthy for the
public," Cheung said at the press conference.
</P>
<P>
"And I think I should learn from the other persons named here
today and contribute to the development and prosperity of Hong
Kong," Cheung added.
</P>
<P>
Dubbed the "King of Canto-Pop," Cheung was named "The World's
Best-Selling Chinese Recording-Artist" in the World Music Awards
in Monte Carlo in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Also named in this year's TOYP Selection were Leon Lai, another
famed singer, Victor Chan, a composer and conductor, Samuel Kwok,
a distinguished colorectal surgeon, Scarlett Pong, a full fledged
registered pharmacist, and Kennedy Wong, a solicitor.
</P>
<P>
The TOYP Selection inaugurated in 1970 has been annually
organized by the Hong Kong Junior Chamber.
</P>
<P>
Honored at the end of the selection are those who have
distinguished themselves in their own professions and have
contributed well to the society.
</P>
<P>
By setting up such examples, the organizers hope to encourage
youngsters to do well in their career and social services and
bear more responsibilities in the social development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
