<HEADLINE> British Prime Minister Tours Nunnery in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 10 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair toured a nunnery in Hong Kong Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Blair and his wife toured the Chi Lin Nunnery in Kowloon in
drizzles and were briefed on the community services of the
nunnery.
</P>
<P>
They also watched the performance of Taiji exercise and
Chinese calligraphy by some old people.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1934, the nunnery has been involved in social and
educational services of the community.
</P>
<P>
The nunnery was rebuilt comprehensively in 1989 into a Tang
Dynasty style monastic complex of timber structure to display the
magnificence and beauty of ancient Chinese architecture.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon, the British visitors toured a busy shopping
center in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The British prime minister is scheduled to conclude his
five-day visit to China and leave Hong Kong for home late
Saturday night.  
</P>
