<HEADLINE> Iranian Court Upholds Death Sentence on German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian court of appeals has
upheld the death sentence on a German businessman for having a
sexual relationship with a Muslim woman, the Iran daily reported
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Helmut Hofer was sentenced to death by an Iranian court last
January after he was arrested at Tehran international airport in
September last year with 26-year-old Bahideh Qassemi, an Iranian
woman.
</P>
<P>
Hofer was convicted of "moral corruption and improper relations
with a young woman," the official newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The court sentenced Qassemi to 100 lashes, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
Qassemi told the court of appeals that when they met at a hotel
in Mashhad, northeastern province of Khorasan, Hofer introduced
himself as a businessman engaged in trade of dried fruits.
</P>
<P>
She said that he promised to employ her in his company in
Mashhad and promised to marry her. But he failed to keep his
promise, she added.
</P>
<P>
Defending himself, Hofer said his relationship with the woman
was a simple friendship, rejecting accusations of illegal sexual
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Under Iranian law, unmarried Muslims who have sex will be
flogged as a punishment. But if the man is a non-Muslim, he will
face death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Hofer's case has aroused Germany's concern. German officials
have warned that the relations between Tehran and Bonn would be
seriously affected if the death sentence on Hofer is carried out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
