<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Offered Lab-Level Nuclear Test Facility by France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- India has been offered by
France to use its laser facility at Bordeaux to conduct
laboratory-scale nuclear tests, "Business Standard" said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Discussions on the issue were held during Indian Prime Minister
Atal Behari Vajpayee's visit in Paris last month as part of the
two countries' cooperation in the nuclear field.
</P>
<P>
The paper said India does not have the technical means to carry
out sub-critical tests at present and it has to spend a lot of
money to set up a particle accelerator or a giant laser facility.
</P>
<P>
India is still unclear what the nature of the French support
will be, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
India announced a moratorium on further nuclear testing after
it conducted five successive underground nuclear tests in May this
year, but it kept the option open to conduct sub-critical nuclear
tests to validate, develop and alter weapons.
</P>
<P>
India will have to conduct sub-critical tests regularly to make
use of the data generated during the May nuclear tests and to
maintain its nuclear weapons program, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
France, as a signatory of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty
(NPT), may run the risk of angering the United States and other
nuclear states by cooperating with India in sub-critical testing,
the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
