<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 09:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen Hails Hanish Arbitration Momentous Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Yemeni Prime Minister Abdul-Karim
al-Eryani Saturday described the international arbitration
decision to restore the Red Sea Hanish Islands to Yemen's
sovereignty as a "momentous victory for Yemeni and Arab diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio broadcasts over
telephone from Sanaa, the capital of Yemen, the premier expressed
hope that the approach both Yemen and Eritrea have adopted to
settle their differences on the islands of Hanish, would provide a
model for the settlement of similar disputes.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Court of Arbitration ruled Friday that disputed
islands in the Red Sea were partly the sovereign territory of
Yemen and partly the sovereign territory of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued from its Hague registry, the tribunal
awarded Eritrea the Mohabbakah islands, some of the Haycock
Islands and the South West Rocks. Yemen gained sovereignty of the
Zuqar-Hanish group, the island of Jaba al-Tayr and the Zubayr
group.
</P>
<P>
On his future vision for Yemeni-Eritrean relations, after the
arbitration decision on Hanish, al-Eryani said that this ruling
will open new vistas for relations between the two countries and
restore them to their past era.
</P>
<P>
The arbitration decision will be implemented within 90 days, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will later present their ideas on their
maritime borders according to the arbitration decision, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
