<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Job Project Launched in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia has launched a
project to offer more jobs aiming at reducing poverty, according
to The Ethiopian Herald.
</P>
<P>
The Jobs for Africa Regional Poverty Reducing Employment
Strategies for Sub-Saharan Africa (JFA-PRESSA) project in
Ethiopia is to put in place poverty reducing employment growth
strategies in ten Sub-Saharan African countries including
Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The project is jointly carried out by International Labor
Organization (ILO) and the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP).
</P>
<P>
Speaking Friday at the launching ceremony for the project,
Wilfred Ndongko, JFA-PRESSA Manager and Technical Advisor, said
that the project is to develop and strengthen the capacity of
national and regional institutions and networks "with a view to
assessing and advocating alternative policies for poverty
reduction through the creation of productive employment".
</P>
<P>
He said this could be achieved at the national level by
establishing national network advocacy groups to assist in the
implementation and monitoring of the program and by disseminating
the application of investment-led poverty reducing employment
strategies.
</P>
<P>
Hassen Abdella, Minister of Labor and Social Affairs of
Ethiopia, said at the meeting that Africa, particularly
Sub-Saharan Africa is confronted with unprecedented social
problems of which unemployment remained among the most
challenging during the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
He said that economic decline accompanied by soaring inflation
and ever-increasing debt burdens have made unemployment a very
serious issue.
</P>
<P>
ILO Area Office Director Vremudia Diejomaoh said on his part
that "even though recent years have witnessed an improvement in
the economic performance of most African countries, the
employment situation still remains grim."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the average rate of urban unemployment in
Africa has almost doubled to about 20 percent over the past 15
years and is projected to approach 30 percent by the year 2000,
adding that Africa is the only region in which the "incidence of
poverty" is projected to increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
