<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Telecommunications Rivals Pick Same Foreign Supplier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- China's two rival
telecommunications companies have recently chosen Canada-based
Nortel Networks as the supplier of equipment and technology for
construction of their respective microwave communications networks.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom and China Unicom are the only two national
companies that provide initial and value-added telecommunications
services for customers in the country.
</P>
<P>
China Telecom placed a 12-million-US-dollar order with Nortel
Networks last month. So far, it has given at least two of its five
open bidding contracts on building digital microwave communication
networks to the Canadian company. Total value of the two contracts
was near 30 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nortel Networks has provided transmission equipment and network
management systems for the four trunk lines of China Telecom's
nation-wide microwave communication network.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom also sealed a contract with Nortel Networks on
purchasing the same microwave equipment and network management
systems last month. The contract value was near 20 million US
dollars. The construction project is a major part of China
Unicom's nationwide distant telephone call network.
</P>
<P>
China Unicom signed another 20-million-US-dollar contract with
Nortel Networks this week. Under the contract, Nortel Networks
will sell GSM equipment to China Unicom for expanding its local
mobile telephone network in east China's Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
Nortel Networks is the new name of the Canadian
telecommunications giant Nortel. Nortel took over Bay Networks in
August and changed its name to Nortel Networks on September 29.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from China's telecommunications industry,
China Telecom and China Unicom are competing intensively in the
fields of long-distance telephone call, mobile communications,
digital microwave communications and data communications.
</P>
<P>
The two companies invested heavily to expand their own specific
telecommunications networks every year. In the past two or three
years, China Telecom spent 11 billion US dollars to introduce
advanced foreign technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
This year, China Unicom obtained the first batch of loan from
the Bank of China, worth about 181 million US dollars. It plans to
complete the construction of a nationwide mobile telephone network
that covers all the major cities in the country. It will also roll
out more than 10,000 km of optic fiber cables throughout the
country by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
China has opened its telecommunications equipment market
completely to the outside world. The Chinese Government has
adopted a strategic policy to encourage introduction of foreign
equipment and technology so as to swiftly lift the technical level
of its telecommunications network to the international standards.
</P>
<P>
At present, international big names such as Motorola, Lucent,
Nortel Networks, Ericsson, Siemens, NEC and Nokia took the lion's
share of China's telecommunications equipment market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
