<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unexpected Slump Hits Title Favorites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Sportswriter Liu Guang
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua)-- Under a cool gray day favored
by marathoners, the pre-game favorites lost their shine as they
failed to display their expected form in the biggest ever
international marathon held in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Hu Gangjun, 28, was helped outside the route at the finish
when a crowd of reporters poured questions upon the winner, a
similar scene when he became the first Chinese to break the
barrier of two hours and 10 minutes in the last edition.
</P>
<P>
Hu, biting his teeth to keep himself within the leading pack
for about 40 minutes, failed to catch the pace since the course
midpoint where he came to a slope.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old kept shaking his head when asked what was
wrong.
</P>
<P>
"I am not certain what the hell is the trouble, for I did
quite well in the training as well as the first half of the
route." said Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hu set his personal mark last year with a time of 2:09:18,
ensuring him the third trophy of the Beijing International
Marathon which dates back to 1981.
</P>
<P>
Hu was not alone at all. Another pre-race favorite, Abebe
Mekonnen of Ethiopia, who had tied the meet's record of 2:07:35
set by Kodama Taisuke of Japan in 1986, also failed to make top
10.
</P>
<P>
Abebe, whose arrival at Beijing was delayed for the death of
his brother, dropped out of the leading field before he reached
halfway.
</P>
<P>
"Both athletes are fresh from the marathon event held two
months ago which made them hard to recover over such a short
time." said the race organizer Shang Xiutang, vice president of
the China Athletics Association.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing International Marathon did not request the
participants should not run for three months before the event,
which is a precondition for any lucrative marathon, Shang said.
</P>
<P>
Shan Changming, Hu Gangjun's coach, argued that the trouble w
ith his student's bad form may lie in his mental state.
</P>
<P>
"I felt a little surprised at his performance, for his
training is quite satisfactory," said the coach. "This had
something to do with his mental quality, we will have a careful
review of the past training."
</P>
<P>
Seeing Hu rise to fame, Shan added that the upcoming Asia
Games was their priority even though this year's race was the
biggest ever.
</P>
<P>
"I had told him before the start not to put too much energy
into the competition if his physical strength failed him, for we
set our sight upon the Asia Games in December."
</P>
<P>
The temperature posted about 16 centigrade with a wind speed
of one meter per second, from which unheralded Kim Jung Won of
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was the biggest b
eneficiary.
</P>
<P>
Kim, 25, surprised the star-studded event by cruising home in
2:13:49, followed by Chang Ki-Shik of South Korea with a time of
2:14.07.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very comfortable with the weather conditions which are
very similar to those in Pyongyang." said Kim, whose personal
best was 2:13.20.
</P>
<P>
Kim, a university student of the physical education, was not
in the DPR Korea's roster for the Bangkok Games.
</P>
<P>
"There are three other athletes whose performance are even
better than his. Two of the three will take part in the Games."
said Pang Mun Il, vice president of the DPR Korea's athletics
association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0126 </DOCNO>
