<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another 2,000 AIDS Cases Found in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has found 2,191 more
people suffering from AIDS in the first half of this year, an
official with the National AIDS Control Program said.
</P>
<P>
Rose Marlene, director of the ADIS control program, said here
Friday that the figure has brought the national total to 8,678
ADIS cases since the first case was found in 1986 in this south
African country, the Noticias newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Of the new patients found, she said, 375 people are children
under four years of age.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that there are about 1.4 million people who
have been found HIV positive among the country's total population
of 15 million.
</P>
<P>
Marlene urged Mozambicans to be more serious about the
disease, saying "we all know that AIDS is fatal, but the biggest
challenge facing us is our attitude to the disease."
</P>
<P>
She said that people must get rid of the cultural and
psycological obstacles in using condoms, the most effective way
to keep people from the killer disease.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
