<HEADLINE> Iran's Envoy for Afghan Affairs Offers Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran's special envoy on the
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi has submitted resignation amid
differences in the Iranian Foreign Ministry on Afghanistan, an
Iranian daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The English-language daily Iran News quoted an informed source
as saying that Boroujerdi's decision was based on the fact that
two policy-making centers exist in the Foreign Ministry on the
affairs in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The current situation in Afghanistan requires unanimity within
the Iranian Foreign Ministry, the source said, adding that
Boroujerdi's resignation is meant to bring about unity in the
ministry vis-a-vis policies and decisions regarding Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The resignation has not yet been accepted, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi, former deputy foreign minister for Asia-Pacific
affairs, came under sharp criticism after eight Iranian diplomats
and a reporter were killed by the Afghan Taliban militia in August
in northern Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He was blamed for inaccurate assessment about the situation in
the neighbor when the Taliban attacked the Iranian-backed
opposition Northern Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The envoy argued that the decision to keep 10 diplomats in
Mazari Sharif in northern Afghanistan on the eve of Taliban's
attack was based on previous experience that the group did not
offend Iranian diplomats in other cities they occupied.
</P>
</TEXT>
