<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soybean, Corn Prices Rise on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Soybean futures rocketed
higher and corn futures advanced remarkably Friday on the Chicago
Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
The soybean price for November delivery rose 23.5 cents to 5.64
U.S. dollars a bushel. The December corn price rose 4.25 cents to
2.215 dollar a bushel.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts noted the price increases occurred after the
U.S. government released its new estimates for the nation's crops.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, the U.S. Agriculture Department cut its
estimate for U.S. soybean production by 5 percent to 2.769 billion
bushels, and left virtually unchanged its estimate of 9.734 billion
bushels for corn production.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also predicted the amount of soybeans
left over before the 1999 harvest will fall to 396 million bushels
from 485 million as predicted a month ago, and said farmers now
should fetch an average 5.7 U.S. dollars a bushel instead of 5.35
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Most market analysts, however, had predicted the government
would slightly increase its previous estimate of a 2.91
billion-bushel soybean crop.
</P>
<P>
As for corn estimate, market participants had expected a sharp
increase, with some predicting a 10 billion bushel crop.
</P>
<P>
The government said the late-season dry and hot weather helped
sharply reduce pod counts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
