<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Upgrades Scientific, Technological Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A report from the State
Statistics Bureau (SSB) shows that China has significantly
upgraded its levels of science and technology since the
introduction of reform and opening policies in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that some two million people were involved in
the nation's scientific and technological activities in 1997,
including 1.68 million scientists and engineers. Figures also show
that a large number of university graduates were involved in
research. China's colleges and universities graduated 876,000
students in 1997, up 34.8 percent on the figure for 1990.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has also increased investment in the
sector, with 39.4 billion yuan in 1997, representing a 2.8-fold
rise on the 1990 figure.
</P>
<P>
China made 436,000 scientific and technological research
achievements in the 1981-1997 period, with the nation gaining an
international reputation for technological levels in the sectors
of atomic energy, bioengineering and computer sciences.
</P>
<P>
The SSB report notes that China has extended great efforts to
promote practical applications of scientific achievements,
benefiting greatly Chinese enterprises. China now has 60,000
agents for trade of scientific and technological
achievements. And, some 360,000 such achievements have been
patented since 1985, when the Patent Law was put into practrice.
</P>
<P>
China has established ties of cooperation with 150 countries
and regions in the sector of sciences and technology,
with 200 Chinese scientists currently working in international
scientific institutions. SSB figures show that China exported
high-tech products valued at 52 billion US dollars between
1987 and 1997, with the average annual growth rate hitting 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The SSB notes that the reforms have greatly accelerated China's
scientific development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
