<HEADLINE> Carlsberg Brewery Sets Up Shanghai Subsidiary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- A new subsidiary of the Danish
brewing giant Carlsberg Brewery went into operation recently in
Shanghai, China's leading commercial and industrial center.
</P>
<P>
Carlsbrew Brewery (Shanghai), which cost 60 million US dollars
to build, is designed to have an annual brewing capacity of
300,000 tons. It will employ equipment, technology and raw
materials imported from Europe to produce Carlsberg beer to supply
the markets in east and north China.
</P>
<P>
A new brand -- Karhu Beer -- is also expected to be produced.
</P>
<P>
The new facility is jointly invested by Carlsberg Hongkong and
a Shanghai company, with investment from Hong Kong accounting for
95 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is the second Carlsberg brewery on the Chinese mainland. The
first is located in Huizhou, Guangdong Province. To date,
Carlsberg has injected about one billion yuan (120.48 million US
dollars) on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
China's beer consumption has been growing at an annual rate of
20 percent since 1979. In 1997, beer sales of the country
exceeded 160 million liters, of which Shanghai accounted for 30
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
