<HEADLINE> Container Shipping Grows in Shenzhen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Ports in the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone handled 1.36 million TEUs in the first nine months
of this year, as compared with 1.14 million TEUs in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Local port authorities predict that the zone adjacent to Hong
Kong will handle 1.8 million TEUs this year, 58 percent up on last
year's figure.
</P>
<P>
With several fine container terminals, Shenzhen now has the
second largest container handling capacity among coastal Chinese
cities.
</P>
<P>
The fine conditions and favorable geological position of the
Shenzhen ports are attractive to Hong Kong investors. At present,
two of Shenzhen's largest container terminals, Yantian in the east
and Shekou in the west, are respectively operated by two of the
Hong Kong giants, the Hutchison Whampoa and Swire Pacific groups.
</P>
<P>
The city now is preparing to set up an ocean-shipping exchange
to further boost the shipping sector, city officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
