<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15,000 Bangladeshi Women, Children Smuggled out Every </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Approximately 15,000 Bangladeshi
women and children are smuggled out every year and the traffickers
use the country as a transit point of human trade, The Financial
Express newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a study conducted by the Center for Women and Children
Studies in Dhaka, the newspaper said massive poverty and AIDS-free
physique of Bangladeshi girls impelled the human traffickers to
smuggle and force them into flesh trade abroad.
</P>
<P>
The study suggests an integrated national policy against child
and women trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The trafficking in women and children for prostitution, forced
labor and slavery reached an alarming proportion now, the study
noted.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Bangladeshi under-aged girls trafficked to
different countries were engaged in prostitution in brothels, the
study said.
</P>
<P>
Children between six and 15 suffered sexual abuses, and some
died either from physical or sexual assaults or during journey
from their homes, it said.
</P>
<P>
Some of the key factors related to trafficking were identified
as poverty, gender discrimination and lower status of the girl
child, allurement of jobs and marriages, and strong networks of
traffickers both within and without the country, it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The law-enforcing agencies have a poor performance in combating
the human smuggling, and only nine percent of the missing children
were rescued by them, the study said.
</P>
<P>
From January 1990 to September 1997, the study said, some 2,622
children were missing and 845 kidnapped, and only 228 and 512 of
them were later rescued by the law-enforcing agencies. The rest
were still missing or lured for good jobs into mainly India,
Pakistan and the Middle East, the study found, quoting officials
at the Social Welfare Department.
</P>
<P>
The male children were made into jockeys for camel race in the
Middle East while the girls and women ended up in red-light
quarters or often forced into slavery, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 Bangladeshi women and children have been
trafficked to the Middle East and India in the past 20 years, and
around 20,000 Bangladeshi women are involved in prostitution in
Indian brothels alone, according to human rights organizations and
newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government is very much concerned about the
growing trend in women and children trafficking and has taken a
series of stern measures in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0138 </DOCNO>
