<HEADLINE> U.S. Cities Bidding 2012 Olympics Get More Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The nine American cities
bidding to host the 2012 Summer Olympics were given more time
Friday to come up with government guarantees to back their bids.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Olympic Committee policy-making panel set December 31
as the new deadline for the bidders to obtain city or regional
government acknowledgment that tax money could be require to
cover any budget shortfall a privately financed Games might
encounter.
</P>
<P>
Four others - Baltimore-Washington, New York, San Francisco
and Seattle - had obtained promises of council consideration of
the commitment, while the ninth, Los Angeles, had no such action.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl said the nine bid
packages submitted by the September 30 deadline all looked di
fferent. USOC executive director Dick Schultz said only one of
the nine cities had submitted a complete and fully documented
package. He declined to say which city that was.
</P>
<P>
The USOC won't pick its bid city until the fall of 2002 and
the IOC doesn't make the final choice until 2005. 
</P>
