<HEADLINE> hke101019 -Vietnamese Leaders Want to Improve Relations with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese Communist Party
General Secretary Le Kha Phier has said Vietnam is willing to
develop friendship and cooperation with the United States on the
basis of mutual respect and benefit, Press reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese party general secretary made the remarks when
meeting visiting President of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce Thomas
J. Donohue here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Phieu said he hoped that U.S. investors will strengthen
cooperation with Vietnam, and believed that the two countries will
reach a trade agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam would continue to improve its investment environment,
Phieu said, adding that he wished that foreign investors should
consider the level of socio-economic development and state
management capacity of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Donohue said that the U.S. Chamber of Commerce now it is urging
the U.S. government to sign a trade agreement between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Donohue added that many American companies and enterprises are
prepared to cooperate with Vietnam, and wished for the country's
continuation to improve its investment environment in the fields
of law, trade, finance, banking, administrative procedures.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai also met Donohue here
Friday. Khai expressed his hope that the chamber president himself
and U.S. businessmen would further contribute to an early signing
of a trade agreement between the two nations, making it a legal
basis for large-scale investment and trade, especially in
investment capital, technology and management.
</P>
<P>
Donohue expressed the wishes of the U.S. businessmen to expand
cooperative ties with the country not only in the economic field
but also in technology and services.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce has had more than 500 member
companies including multinational giants operating in Hanoi and Ho
Chi Minh city since the two countries established diplomatic
relations in July 1995.
</P>
<P>
The two-way trade value between Vietnam and the United States
was over 1 billion U.S. dollars in 1997, and the U.S. is now the
tenth biggest investor in Vietnam with a total investment capital
of 1.1 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
