<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPR Korean Surprise Winner at Beijing Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Unheralded runner Kim Jung Won
from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea surprised himself
by beating a strong field to win the men's event at the Beijing
marathon races here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Kim, following closely South Korean Chang Ki-Shik after the
33-kilometer mark, steadily pulled away in the last four
kilometers and cruised home in a time of two hours, thirteen
minutes and 49 seconds, 29 seconds outside of his personal best.
</P>
<P>
Chang came second in 2:14.07 and Brazilian Osmiro De Souza
Silva was third 2:14.26.
</P>
<P>
"I dedicate my success to our great leader Kim II Sung and the
people in our country," Kim said after the unexpected triumph,
"The weather conditions in Beijing are quite similar with that in
Pyongyang, so I feel very comfortable."
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old student majoring in physical education at the
DPR Korean University was running against a legion of
high-profile athletes including Abebe Mekonnen of Ethiopia, who
still has the event's best time of 2:07.35 to his credit, local
hero and defending champion Hu Gangjun and a seven-man Kenyan
group headed by Peter Kimeli Chemei whose personal best is
2:09.53.
</P>
<P>
Under gray but calm skies, the race started to unfold at the
halfway point with a 10-man group breaking away from the rest of
the field.
</P>
<P>
By 35km, the leading pack had been reduced to two men and it
became clear the battle for men's gold and 20,000 prize money
came down to a fight between the diminutive DPR Korean and the
lanky South Korean.
</P>
<P>
The pre-meet favorite Abebe and Hu, who fell away after the
midway point, both finished outside top 10.
</P>
<P>
In the women's event, home favorite Wang Yanrong made a
explosive move just ahead of the finish line to steal the gold
from Russian Lioubov Mirgouonova.
</P>
<P>
Wang, whose personal best was 2:38.18, burst past the Russian
for the victory in 2:28.50, just one second clear of the Russian.
Jong Song Ok from DPR Korea claimed the bronze in 2:30.48.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Chinese runner, whose toes were bleeding
because of injury, attributed her win to courage brought about by
a cheering crowd at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
"Courage helped me win the race," she said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20,000 people took part in the competition, biggest
ever in its 17-year history, which also included half marathon,
10km marathon and mini-marathon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
