<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Flood Investment Scope Makes Bangladesh's Banking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The recent severe floods, which
battered the economy of Bangladesh, could hardly affect the
banking sector as the need for post-flood rehabilitation and food
imports offered new business opportunities to avert possible
fallout of a disaster-driven economic stagnation, The Financial
Express daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see the banks were affected anyway by the floods.
Rather, I see a lot of business opportunities in the coming days
to use their idle funds," the daily quoted a bank managing
director as saying.
</P>
<P>
Both the government and private sector traders had been
importing huge amount of foodgrains following crop losses caused
by the century's worst floods, he observed.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government was disbursing a huge amount of money
among the farmers through banks to enable them to overcome the
crop losses, he said, adding that the business relating to
rehabilitation of damaged infrastructure and affected sectors
would be an additional opportunity for the banks.
</P>
<P>
The banks would have to defer repayment schedule of loans for
the borrowing industries in line with the three-month moratorium
announced by the government recently, another bank managing
director noted.
</P>
<P>
It would be a loss from the banking point of view, he said,
pointing out that repayment of nearly 630 million taka (about 13.4
million U.S. dollars) loan to his bank alone would have to be
deferred due to floods.
</P>
<P>
The impact of the deferred repayment would hardly affect banks'
financial health, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
The economic stagnation caused by the deluge had squeezed
business opportunities for the banking sector, but additional food
imports and post-flood rehabilitation activities would help
overcome the loss, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the banking sector would have to disburse
loans worth 30 billion taka (about 638.3 million dollars) among
farmers as part of the government's agricultural rehabilitation
plan and the central bank would refinance the banks.
</P>
<P>
The banks remained unaffected by the devastating floods as
exports after initial disruptions continued under special
arrangement and import of grains also helped them to overcome the
loss of business in other sectors, a central bank official said.
</P>
<P>
The post-flood rehabilitation would bring momentum in the
banking business, he said, adding that the need for working
capital to fix flood-caused damage to the industries would help
the banks to use their idle money.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector has now a liquidity surplus of 26.98 billion
taka (about 574 million dollars), the central bank official
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary estimate puts the total loss caused by the
ten-week-long devastating flood at around 4.3 billion dollars,
about 10 percent of the country's GDP (gross domestic product),
according to the latest figure released by the Planning Ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
