<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President Ends Visit to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- South Korea President Kim Dae
Jung concluded his four-day state visit to Japan and left Japan's
western industrialized city of Osaka for home on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving Osaka, the last leg of his four-day visit to
Japan, Kim said his state visit to Japan was "a great success."
</P>
<P>
He made the remark to more than 700 Korean residents in Osaka,
home to the largest Korean community in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Kim arrived in Osaka on Friday following what he termed a
successful visit to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
While in Tokyo, Kim and Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
agreed to cooperate in building a "new partnership toward the 21st
century."
</P>
<P>
In their declaration, Obuchi expressed Japan's "deep remorse
and heartfelt apology" to the South Korean people for the "great
pains and damage" inflicted on them during Japan's colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
This was Japan's strongest apology in 33 years. Japan exercised
colonial rule over the Korean Peninsula from 1910 to 1945. 
</P>
</TEXT>
