<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, October 10 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- A total of 5.043 million foreign tourists arrived in
Thailand in the first eight months this year, an increase of 5.59
percent compared with the same period last year, according to the
Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT).
</P>
<P>
Thailand is one of the few countries in Asia to report growth
in Tourist arrivals this year. (Thailand-Tourism)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The ongoing monetary crisis in Indonesia has caused
the decline in investments, especially foreign direct investments
which decreased by 48.6 percent in value, the Indonesian Observer
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Actually there are 565 projects with direct foreign
investments approved by the government, increasing by 25.5 percent
from last year's figure, but the value of the projects declined by
48.6 percent to 24 billion U.S. dollars," secretary of the
Investment Coordinating Board Mohammad Syukur said.
(Indonesia-Foreign Investments)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Ministers of the Organization for Economic
Cooperation and Development (OECD) ended their two-day meeting on
electronic commerce here today, without much concrete to show back
at home.
</P>
<P>
"Elements of a 'shared vision' for global electronic commerce
emerged from the conference," said an OECD news release issued at
the end of the gathering. (Canada-OECD-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. cotton production fell 2 percent this
month, due partly to poor weather conditions, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's cotton-growing regions such as Georgia's cotton
production dropped 50,000 bales from last month and Texas'
harvested acres declined 250,000 acres. (US-Agriculture)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- Canada is heading into a "mild recession" in 1999,
according to a new economic outlook.
</P>
<P>
The gloomy forecast, from J.P Morgan Securities Canada Inc., is
believed to be the first to predict that Canada will experience
not just a slowdown in growth, but a shrinkage of gross domestic
product (GDP). (Canada-Economy-Forecast)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Losses of other Asian markets will mean India's
gains, as India is poised to be the big beneficiary of the
currency meltdown in the region, said a report here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Equity sell-off and currency falls across Asia have left India
with the third-highest capitalized market behind Hong Kong and
Taiwan, said the report by the All India Association of
Industries. (India-Asia-Market) 
</P>
</TEXT>
