<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Earns From Fish Products Export Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has earned 33 million
U.S. dollars from the export of fisheries products in the first
six months this year as against 30.2 million dollars in the same
period last year, according to the Fisheries Ministry here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The fish and fisheries product sector in the country had been
identified as one of the priority sectors for development due to
its export potential and high employment generation capacity, the
ministry sources said.
</P>
<P>
Over the last few years there had been a rapid development in
shrimp farming and a significant growth in the export of fish and
fisheries products.
</P>
<P>
Though the fisheries industry mainly caters to the local market
at present, high valued products such as tuna, prawns, lobsters
and crabs are exported to Japan, the U.S. and Europe, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years there has been a significant growth
of exports of fisheries products. In 1997, Sri Lanka earned 65.3
million dollars, a growth of six percent over 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
