<HEADLINE> Italian President to Mediate Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro will have a busy agenda trying to resolve the current
government crisis in the wake of Prime Minister Romano Prodi's
resignation on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prodi lost the vote of confidence in the Lower House of
parliament by 313 votes to 312. He then handed in his
resignation, which had already been accepted by President Scalfaro.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro asked Prodi to head a caretaker government pending his
replacement. The president has until November 24 to decide
whether to form a new government or call for early elections.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet first Senate Speaker Nicola Mancino and
then House Speaker Luciano Violante on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, he will discuss with representatives from political
forces of both the opposition Freedom Front and the just-defeated
leftist Olive Tree coalition that formed Prodi's government.
</P>
<P>
Scalfaro will also consult with former heads of state Giovanni
Leone and Francesco Cossiga.
</P>
<P>
The departure of Prodi, who came to power in May 1996, leaves
Italy without leadership at a time when crucial budgetary problems
loom and tough decisions need to be made on possible NATO air
strikes on Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis and the country's
entry into the European single currency on January 1, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
