<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke101013-India to Announce Anti-Dumping Duty on Hot-Rolled Coils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Indian Union Commerce
Ministry is expected to announce anti-dumping duty on hot-rolled
coil imports from the Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) by
the end of this month, official sources said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian steel industry had filed for imposition of
anti-dumping duty in March 1997. The industry is planning to file
similar complaints against imports from other countries as well
once the decision on CIS imports is taken. On the firing line are
Japan, South Korea and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The domestic steel industry is passing through its lowest ebb
ever reflecting a similar trend in the global markets. What has
compounded the problem is the large-scale dumping of steel on
India. The duty is expected to help the troubled Indian steel
industry face competition from imports, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The global average ex-plant cost of production of steel is 301
U.S. dollars per ton. After the freight and shipping costs are
factored in, the landed price in India should be 361 dollar per
ton. The current price levels, however, are in the range of
220-240 dollars per ton, the sources further said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
