<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Suspends Rome Laboratory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) Medical Commission has suspended the Acqua
Acetosa Laboratory in Rome.
</P>
<P>
The Chairman of the IOC Medical Commission, Prince Alexandre
de Merode, announced on Friday that the laboratory will not be
able to present itself for re-accreditation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Italian National Olympic Committee (CONI) will, however,
be able to continue conducting doping control activities by
sending its samples to IOC-accredited laboratories, Prince de
Merode said.
</P>
<P>
Prince de Merode stressed that the Rome laboratory will, after
a period of three months, have the opportunity to present a new
candidature for accreditation, provided that the instructions
which have been communicated to it have been followed.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, CONI's medical commission said Acqua Acetosa
Laboratory will be shut down for allegedly cover-up of doping
tests in soccer.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the doping tests of Italian League soccer had not
been fully carried out and the results may have been hidden.
Documentation of anti-doping tests, which was required to keep at
least two years, was being discarded after two months, with five
in the case of positive tests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
