<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moldova Vows to Stabilize Its Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Moldova
will take every possible measure to stabilize its currency, the
governor of the central bank Leonid Talmaci said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
He admitted, however, that it is difficult to stop the
devaluation of the country's currency in the short term.
</P>
<P>
According to Rompress news agency, the Moldovan leu fell
sharply this week. The exchange rate of the leu to the dollar
dropped from 5.0055 to 1, to 5.2 to 1, below the "psychological
resistance line" of 5 to 1, and the devaluation is likely to
continue.
</P>
<P>
The government and the central bank are striving to keep its
currency no lower than 5.5 to the dollar. But financial experts
here said that the goal is hard to achieve in the absence of a
loan of nearly 100 million dollars the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund had earlier promised.
</P>
<P>
One month ago, the leu's value became unstable due to the
financial crisis in Russia. The central bank quickly stabilized it
by selling dollars in considerable amounts along with some
commercial banks and closed more than 20 foreign exchanges for
"disturbing the exchange market." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
