<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Children Illiterate Reaches 14 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 10 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen percent of Sri Lankan
children are illiterate despite free education in the country
since the 1950s, according to the Education Ministry here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Most children keep away from school due to abject poverty and
are compelled to work instead for their home life, the ministry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Deputy Minister of Education Viswa Warnapala
as saying that schooling was not a privilege but a right of every
child and this right should not be denied to the child either by
the state or the parents.
</P>
<P>
The government will soon bring legislation to make schooling
compulsory for children between the ages of 5 and 14 years of age,
according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
To save the children morals must be inculcated as they mature
both in homes and schools. The responsibility must be equally
shared by the state and the parents as well as the teachers, the
sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
