<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Cautious With Possible Kosovo Intervention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria will be cautious about
joining any possible military action in Kosovo, said Prime
Minister Ivan Kostov here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody has wanted Bulgaria to join an armed intervention in
Kosovo yet," Kostov said in parliament in response to a statement
of the Democratic Left pressing the government for a categorical
"no" to any request for intervention in the turbulent Yugoslav
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Kostov said that the government has not received any request
from NATO (North Atlantic Treaty Organization) Secretary-General
Javier Solana, who has been authorized by the NATO Council to seek
permission from Albania, Macedonia, Bulgaria, Romania and Hungary
to allow NATO's aircraft to fly over their territories.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the government is ready to deal with such requests,
Kostov said the government will act very reasonably and cautiously
at this moment.
</P>
<P>
If such a request is made, the government will handle it
according to the procedures established by the Constitution as it
has always done, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Kostov reiterated that Bulgaria has joined the concerted
efforts of its neighbors for a peaceful solution to the conflict
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Friday, the Left asked the National Assembly to
appeal to the parliaments of the southeast European countries to
find a comprehensive, just and peaceful solution to the conflict
in Kosovo and to voice unconditional support to the multinational
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
"The Democratic Left believes that the conflict in Kosovo
threatens Bulgaria's national security," Socialist MP Ivan Genov
said at an earlier news conference.
</P>
<P>
According to Bulgarian media reports, cabinet members are
underestimating the danger of the Kosovo conflict and have
indicated their intention to revise Bulgaria's position, adopted
by a consensus in 1993, on non-interference and non-involvement in
military actions in former Yugoslavia in any form, either direct
or indirect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
