<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Considers Independent Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Talk of
performance-enhancing drugs has dominated sports headlines this
year as much as sexual misconduct gossip dominated political
headlines.
</P>
<P>
Was the use of the supplement androstenedione, a precursor to
testosterone that is banned in many sports, fired Mark McGwire's
baseball home-run record?
</P>
<P>
And while track star Florence Griffith Joyner denied taking
performance-enhancing drugs, rumors that began with her startling
performances a decade ago, escalated with her premature death
last month.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Olympic Committee has steered clear of much of the
controversy - it has no control over U.S. professional sports, or
cycling's Tour de France, which erupted in scandal over the use
of the synthetic hormone EPO this year.
</P>
<P>
But USOC controls U.S. Olympic hopefuls, and as it goes into
its annual Olympic Congress meetings this weekend in Phoenix, the
organization is considering a plan that could improve its drugs
testing methods.
</P>
<P>
Within the next few weeks, USOC President Bill Hybl will
appoint a committee to look at bids and study the feasibility of
hiring an independent agency to handle its drug testing.
</P>
<P>
It would conduct random tests, collect urine samples,
transport the samples to the two International Olympic C
ommittee-approved laboratories in the USA and nitify sports
federations if an athlete tests positive.
</P>
<P>
The idea, said USOC executive director Dick Schultz, is "to
get rid of the perception that we've got the fox in the henhouse."
</P>
<P>
The plan is similar to one proposed by the IOC, which runs the
Olympics and controls Olympic testing and financing.
</P>
<P>
In August, the IOC announced a plan to set up a independent
group to conduct worldwide random testing. But it will not start
to work out details until February 2 at a meeting in
Lausanne,Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
It faces a huge task of getting international goernming bodies
to agree to a standardized plan.
</P>
<P>
USOC's plan doesn't challenge the IOC's. "What we'd do would
be over and above," Schultz said, adding he'd like to get a
proposal together in time for consideration at the April 1999
Board of Directors meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
