agreement on an aid package to help Brazil surmount the financial
crisis it has been suffering for the last two months.
</P>
<P>
The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange, the most important one in Latin
America, closed 2.30 percent higher at mid-session on Friday.
Trading stood at 175 million reals (150 million U.S. dollars)
three hours after its opening.
</P>
<P>
The Rio de Janeiro Stock Exchange also showed a 1.8-percent
gain by mid-session Friday. 
