<HEADLINE> Chile to Cut Defense Budget by 3 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Chile's 1999 defense budget
will be cut by 3 percent due to a reduction in military personnel
and the impact of the Asian crisis on the country, a senior
defense planner said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The military budget was also affected by a rising dollar
against the local currency, which will reduce the real spending on
military equipment by nearly 10 percent in terms of dollars, said
Francisco Encina, president of the Defense Commission in the
Chamber of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 defense budget stands at 1.71 billion dollars, most of
it for salaries, while what would be cut is the spending for
operations and expenditures of other kinds, he said.
</P>
<P>
Encina also said that military personnel must be reduced to
modernize the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Number of the country's navy staff members will go down from
29,000 to 23,000 in five years and the army also plans to reduce
its number of personnel, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
