<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sweden Urges Yugoslavia to Manage to Avoid NATO Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Swedish Minister of Foreign
Minister Anna Lindh Friday appealed to Yugoslavia to avoid
possible NATO air strikes by accepting the demand of the
international community to end the bloodshed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the U.N. Security Council, Sweden is ready to
participate in the making of a decision on a military action to
force Belgrade to fulfill a binding Security Council resolution,
Lindh was quoted as saying by the Swedish news media.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly hope that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
take steps to avoid the occurrence of such a situation," she said.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, U.S. State Department spokesman James Foley said
that the ongoing talks between U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and
Milosevic over Kosovo on Friday in Belgrade were tough but
inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Holbrooke told me that those were very intense
discussions and tough going. He did not, to me, characterize
either positively or negatively those discussions except to say
that they will resume," he added.
</P>
<P>
"He's highly focused on the matter at hand, which is trying to
persuade Mr. Milosevic to comply in a thoroughgoing, durable,
verifiable way. And it's hard work. And he's not there. And so he
remains in Belgrade," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke spent 3 1/2 hours trying to persuade Milosevic to
comply with U.N. demands on the province of Kosovo. Holbrooke's
previous rounds of talks with Milosevic made no progress.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. asks Belgrade to comply fully with the U.N. Security
Council Resolution that demands Yugoslavia end fighting in Kosovo,
withdraw its troops, allow relief groups access to refugees and
begin negotiating a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, a NATO official said Friday that the alliance was
expected to issue the order that would activate the phased air
strikes it has threatened for almost seven months.
</P>
<P>
But the issue of the activation order will not immediately lead
to actual air-borne attacks, the official hinted after the day's
two sessions of the North Atlantic Council, the decision-making
body of the western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO has amassed a total of 340 warplanes including 260 from
the United States that provided the NATO air strike operation with
two B-2 Stealth bombers and six B-52 bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
