<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke101004-Indonesia's Foreign Investments Drop by 48 Pct in Value </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing monetary crisis in
Indonesia has caused the decline in investments, especially
foreign direct investments which decreased by 48.6 percent in
value, the Indonesian Observer reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Actually there are 565 projects with direct foreign
investments approved by the government, increasing by 25.5 percent
from last year's figure, but the value of the projects declined by
48.6 percent to 24 billion U.S. dollars," secretary of the
Investment Coordinating Board Mohammad Syukur said.
</P>
<P>
He said that domestic investment approvals this year reached
553 projects valued at 91.4 trillion rupiah (9.1 billion U.S.
dollars), meaning it declined by 57.5 percent in the number of
projects and by 40.2 percent in the value in comparison with the
figure for 1997.
</P>
<P>
The decline on total investments has made the government focus
its policies in bringing back the investor confidence by creating
a favorable condition on the investment climate, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
