<HEADLINE> Mexican President to Urge G-7 Leadership in Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo will urge the Group of Seven (G-7) major industrialized
countries to assume leadership in the global financial crisis when
he visits Britain next week, official sources said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to Foreign Minister Rosario Green, Zedillo will meet
with British Prime Minister Tony Blair during his five-day visit
starting on Monday, seeking to "promote a strong leadership of the
Group of Seven in the present financial crisis."
</P>
<P>
Zedillo will then head for Oporto, Portugal, to attend the
eighth Ibero-American summit, where he is expected to reiterate
the call for the G-7 countries to table concrete policies and
contribute more money to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican president will also use the Ibero-American Summit
forum to voice his complaint that Latin America has been treated
unfairly in the ongoing financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Latin America has been implementing for more than a decade
programs of adjustment, structural reforms and a budget discipline
that have permitted it to return to the road of growth despite the
political cost. This (the financial crisis) makes it feel that it
is being treated unjustly," Green said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
