<HEADLINE> Spain to Participate in NATO Air Strikes on Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish government announced
Friday that Spain will participate in possible air strikes against
Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, a government spokesman,
however, said NATO's use of military force against Yugoslavia can
be realized only when all political and diplomatic efforts have
failed.
</P>
<P>
Before the use of force, the NATO members must reach clear-cut
and unified understanding on whether all diplomatic channels have
been used out, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that this position of the Spanish government
and its offer to participate in possible air strikes are intended
to strengthen the ongoing "diplomatic efforts" to seek a peaceful
settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish military revealed earlier that four Spanish F-18
jets were placed on standby and were ready to participate in
military actions against Yugoslavia once NATO made a decision.
</P>
<P>
In Brussels, a NATO official said Friday that the alliance was
expected to issue the order that would activate the phased air
strikes it has threatened for almost seven months.
</P>
<P>
But the issue of the activation order will not immediately lead
to actual air-borne attacks, the official hinted after the day's
two sessions of the North Atlantic Council, the decision-making
body of the western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
NATO ambassadors are due to meet for certain on Saturday and on
Sunday as well if need arises, the official said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
"Decision is imminent and decision can be taken quickly," said
the official who explained that the activation order would
authorize the supreme commander of Europe to deliver the planned
air strikes.
</P>
<P>
NATO has amassed a total of 340 warplanes including 260 from
the United States that provided the NATO air strike operation with
two B-2 Stealth bombers and six B-52 bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
