<HEADLINE> Adams out of England Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- England manager Glenn Hoddle had
mixed news on Friday when Tony Adams was ruled out of England's
Euro 2000 match with Bulgaria and Darren Anderton was declared
fit.
</P>
<P>
Both players had been struggling with injury and underwent
late fitness tests ahead of Saturday's qualifier at Wembley.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal defender Adams failed to overcome a back injury and
has been sidelined for the game.
</P>
<P>
He is likely to be replaced by either teammate Martin Keown or
Gary Neville, who has impressed in the center of defense for
Manchester United this season.
</P>
<P>
Adams will stay with the squad and could be available for
Wednesday's match with Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
Injury-plagued midfielder Anderton, who was struggling with a
groin injury and seemed to have again fallen foul of his fitness
jinx, is almost certain to make manager Hoddle's side after
coming through a tough fitness test.
</P>
<P>
It was feared Anderton's problem might have been similar to
the injury that wrecked his playing career in the two seasons b
etween his successful appearances at Euro 96 and the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
He is believed to have been seeing faith healer Eileen Drewery
this week after picking up the injury.
</P>
<P>
Anderton's recovery is good news for Hoddle - but the coach is
without several other midfielders.
</P>
<P>
Paul Ince and David Beckham are suspended, David Batty has
only just returned after injury, Rob Lee is struggling with a
virus and Ray Parlour has been sent back to Arsenal after failing
to shake off an ankle injury. 
