<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ince out Till June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- England midfielder Paul Ince
will not play a competitive match for his country until next June
after he was given a three-match ban following his sending off
against Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Ince landed an automatic suspension for one game for the red
card.
</P>
<P>
UEFA's disciplinary committee gave him a further two-match ban
for comments he made in Italian to referee Pierluigi Collina as
he left the pitch in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
European football's governing body also decided to fine the
Football Association for crowd trouble at September's European
Championship match.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool star Ince will miss England's qualifying games
against Bulgaria on Saturday, Luxembourg next Wednesday and
Poland on March 27.
</P>
<P>
The next competitive game he will be available for is the
return qualifier at home to Sweden on June 5.
</P>
<P>
England manager Glenn Hoddle said: "It is bad news for England
but I can't say I'm surprised.
</P>
<P>
"UEFA rules make clear the ban that you get for insulting a
referee and that is the punishment which Paul has received. We
are unlikely to appeal.
</P>
<P>
"Once the next few days - and our games with Bulgaria and
Luxembourg - are over, I shall be talking to Paul again, " he
added.
</P>
<P>
Football Association director of public affairs David Davies
denied that the ban had anything to do with Ince's alleged
'V-sign'towards the England bench.
</P>
<P>
And he dismissed claims that England, who have had players
sent off in their last two matches, had become an undisciplined
team.
</P>
<P>
"It is always very easy when you have a spate of disciplinary
incidents like we've had in recent weeks to think that discipline
is getting worse," Davies said.
</P>
<P>
"But if you talk to professionals who were playing the game in
the '50s and 60s, they will tell you that discipline hasn't chan
ged at all.
</P>
<P>
"What has changed over the years is that the rules and the way
they are imposed and the media's focus on the game has increased
out of all recognition."
</P>
<P>
UEFA also decided to fine the FA 60,000 Swiss francs (27,000
U.S. dollars by UEFA for racist chanting by England fans at
Sweden's Henrik Larsson and damage caused to the Rasunda Stadium
in Stockholm by supporters.
</P>
<P>
But Davies said the FA would react to the decision: "We will
most certainly be appealing against the part of the fine that r
elates to racist chanting." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
