<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Support Rate for NZ Major Opposition Party Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 10 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Party, the Major
opposition party in New Zealand, has vaulted ahead to 48 percent
support, according to the results of an opinion poll taken by the
National Business Review-Consultus (NBR) between October 1 and 6.
</P>
<P>
This is the first survey conducted after the New Zealand
National Minority government announced its "Policies For Progress"
last week.
</P>
<P>
According to the scheme, the government intends to lower the
floor for superannuation from 65 percent of the average wage to 60
percent, offending a lot of pensioners.
</P>
<P>
The NBR poll showed the support rate for the ruling National
Party slumped six percentage points to 31 percent, while the
Labor Party, which has led the assault against the changes to
future pensions, gained six percentage points in its support
rate.
</P>
<P>
The Alliance and ACT both slipped in the poll by one percentage
point to eight percent and five percent respectively, while the NZ
First gained one point to three percent.
</P>
<P>
The results of the poll showed in Auckland, the National Party
trailed the Labor Party by 35 percent to 44 percent and in the
provinces it was also well behind on 32 percent compared to Labor
Party's 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Wellington, the Labor Party recorded 45 percent against
National Party's 28 percent and in Christchurch the Labor Party
was on 54 percent compared to the National Party on 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
The NBR said the National Party had majority support only among
top income earners, where it polled 43 percent to the Labor
Party's 29 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
