<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agent Prepares to Filed Grievance for Some Players </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The unity that NBA players
have shown during the owner-imposed lockout could be at an end.
</P>
<P>
Atlanta-based agent Steve Woods said Thursday that he's
considering filing a grievance with the union on behalf of
several players who are concerned about the labor impasse.
</P>
<P>
Woods told union executive director Billy Hunter of the
unnamed players' concern and plans to file a grievance Monday
unless progress toward an agreement is made.
</P>
<P>
"I've talked to more than 10 players," he says. "The consensus
is their view on unity was based more on solidarity than an
understanding of the owners' proposal and an understanding of the
union's negotiating tactics. The lockout is abstract during the
summer. Now that preseason games are canceled, it's real."
</P>
<P>
Woods says "the union has done a great job representing the
interest of its board members. Playing or not playing does not
represent a real hardship for Ewing. But for a few hundred it
represents a real hardship." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
