<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, a Free Market by Law: Finance Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's law provides that
it should remain a free market and actually it is, said Finance
Secretary Donald Tsang here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is still probably the freest economy in the world
with no restrictions on capital flows, a stable and freely
convertible currency, no restrictions on gold or silver trading,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has no duties payable on virtually all goods, no
trade quotas, he said, noting that what Kong Kong has is a low tax
system, the rule of law and a fast unfettered flow of news and
information.
</P>
<P>
Tsang made the remarks at a luncheon co-hosted by the National
Committee on U.S.-China Relations and the Hong Kong Economic and
Trade Office in New York.
</P>
<P>
Tsang is on a three-week tour of world financial and business
centers to give a factual picture of the economic situation in
Hong Kong and to exchange views on how to stabilize the world
financial market.
</P>
<P>
His trip, kicked off on September 27, has already taken him to
Frankfurt, Munich, the Hague, Amsterdam and Washington.
</P>
<P>
"We thrive on a free market," he said. "We will not impose
capital controls, we have no intention of taking a covert position
in the stock market, we will not devalue the Hong Kong dollar."
</P>
<P>
"It is unfair to judge our commitment to the free market by a
single, extraordinary battle at a time of great economic turmoil,
and when massive, secretive and destructive capital flows were
creating havoc in the markets," said Tsang.
</P>
<P>
The battle was referred to the Hong Kong government's action to
buy shares in August to dispel a handful of speculators who
"threatened Hong Kong's very economic existence."
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that about a week ago the government announced the
establishment of a separate company to professionally manage the
portfolio of shares purchased during the operation.
</P>
<P>
He said the government does not want to seek representation on
the board of those companies in which it has substantial holdings
and that it will disclose the share holdings in due course.
</P>
<P>
Over 150 business leaders attended the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
Tsang will continue his journey in Boston and London and is due
to return to Hong Kong on October 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Talks with Milosevic is Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing talks between
U.S. envoy Richard Holbrooke and Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic over Kosovo on Friday in Belgrade were tough but
inconclusive, the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said he spoke to
Holbrooke at about 1 p.m. local time (1800 GMT).
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Holbrooke told me that those were very intense
discussions and tough going. He did not, to me, characterize
either positively or negatively those discussions except to say
that they will resume," he added.
</P>
<P>
"He's highly focused on the matter at hand, which is trying to
persuade Mr. Milosevic to comply in a thoroughgoing, durable,
verifiable way. And it's hard work. And he's not there. And so he
remains in Belgrade," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke and Milosevic began a second meeting in Belgrade
later on Friday as Western leaders stepped up the pressure for the
Serbians to meet their demands.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke spent 3 1/2 hours trying to persuade Milosevic to
comply with U.N. demands on the province of Kosovo. Holbrooke's
previous rounds of talks with Milosevic made no progress.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. asks Belgrade to comply fully with the U.N. Security
Council Resolution that demands Yugoslavia end fighting in Kosovo,
withdraw its troops, allow relief groups access to refugees and
begin negotiating a final settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global IT Spending Approaching 2 Trillion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Global spending on
information technology (IT) and communications, including internal
corporate spending, reached almost 2 trillion U.S. dollars in
1997, according to a new study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted by the U.S. market researcher
International Data Corporation (IDC) for the World Information
Technology and Services Alliance (WITSA), indicated that the IT
industry was growing at a rate substantially faster than worldwide
gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the results of the study suggest that national GDP
grows when information and communication technology (ICT) spending
increases and that even in the face of worsening economic
conditions, the effect on ICT spending is muted, the WITSA said in
the news release. The WITSA is a consortium of IT industry
associations from economies around the world.
</P>
<P>
The study, based on data gathered in the 50 largest country
markets as well as four rest of region components, shows that the
"information economy" is not a vague abstraction but a powerful
force, contributing 6 percent of aggregate global GDP to the world
economy, the WITSA said.
</P>
<P>
By making a substantial contribution to productivity, the WITSA
said, information and communication technology is helping
countries and companies of all sizes reach their strategic goals.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua in Los Angeles earlier this week,
IDC chairman Patrick McGovern said that computers and network
systems played a big role in raising productivity and enabling the
eight-year consecutive economic growth in the United States. In
fact, he said, IT makes knowledge available for individual workers
and information exchange and coordination possible and efficient
within and among the enterprises. The result is bigger sales and
profits without adding employees.
</P>
<P>
The new study also provides additional evidence of the
mind-boggling growth of personal computers and their influence on
education. At year end 1997, 118 million personal computers had
been installed in homes and educational institutions worldwide, up
from 35 million in 1992. According to IDC forecast, World Wide Web
utilization will hit 100 million people by the end of this year
and 320 million by 2002. Every year, an additional 50 million
people gain access to telephone lines in their homes.
</P>
<P>
In country to country comparisons, the study said that the U.S.
spent 643 billion dollars on ICT in 1997, twice as much as Japan
at 317 billion dollars. These two countries represent 53 percent
of the world marketplace. Other "top five spenders" are Germany,
Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
Asia-Pacific has been the fastest growing ICT market over the
last five years, with Japan, Australia, China and South Korea
among the top spenders. China, ranked in the top 10 ICT markets,
grew at a rate of 28.5 percent, the IDC study said. According to
McGovern, China is expected to become the world's largest ICT
market by 2008. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981010.0210 </DOCNO>
