<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NIST Develops Instruments to Measure Rail Wheel Stress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National Institute
of Standards and Technology (NIST) has developed a system that
could be used to test railway wheel stress that may lead to
cracking and derailment.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued by the NIST, Raymond E.
Schramm from the NIST's Materials Reliability Division, Boulder,
Colorado, has worked out a system whereby ultrasonic waves are
sent through a railroad wheel rim and echoed back. By measuring
the very small difference in travel time of two waves as they pass
through the rim of a railroad wheel, scientists can determine the
hoop stress and the conditions that could lead to cracking and
failure of the entire wheel.
</P>
<P>
The instrumentation package is compact, assembled largely of
commercial electronics, highly automated and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
Two possible uses of the system are in quality control at the
wheel factory and as a screening tool in a shop environment to
evaluate the condition of wheels during routine maintenance and
inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
