<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-09 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2110GMT, October 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Israeli woman was stabbed to death by a
Palestinian in the West Bank Friday and the attacker has been
caught after being shot and wounded by Israeli security forces,
Israel Radio said.
</P>
<P>
The woman was attacked when she was waiting for a bus at a
road crossing near the Jewish settlement of Tomer, north of the
Palestinian town of Jericho.
</P>
<P>
The assailant, who came from a Palestinian village near Tomer,
was caught after Israeli security forces opened fire and hit in
his legs, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses told Israel Radio that the Palestinian man
repeatedly stabbed the woman before she fell to the ground.
(BC-Israel-Soldier-Stabbing 2ndWritethru)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu Friday
named Ariel Sharon, a prominent hardliner in the cabinet, as the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
In a news conference held in the Prime Minister Office,
Netanyahu said that Sharon will assume his post next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sharon will continue to be the minister of national
infrastructure for another three months.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said that the appointment of Sharon is completely in
line with "our desire" for peace.
</P>
<P>
Sharon is considered an influential figure in Israeli politics as
he enjoys wide support among hardliners in the Jewish country.
He has been opposing to making compromise in the negotiations with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He is also the member of Netanyahu's "kitchen cabinet,"
which also includes Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordecai and Trade
Minister Natan Sharansky. (BC-Israel-Sharon-Foreign Minister)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Chairman
Yasser Arafat has condemned the killing of an Israeli woman
soldier Friday by a Palestinian, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Netanyahu as saying that Arafat, who is on
a visit to Russia, condemned the stabbing in a telephone
conversation with him.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu said earlier that the incident underlines Israeli
demands that the PNA uproot terrorism infrastructure on its
territory. Labor Party leader Ehud Barak also said that terrorism
must be fought relentlessly. (BC-Israel-Arafat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Foreign Ministry has expressed "astonishment"
at a statement made by Turkish ambassador in Amman, alleging that
Iraq has contacts with the Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK), outlawed
in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
In a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency Friday, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman termed the Turkish allegations as
groundless.
</P>
<P>
Since the Gulf War in which Iraqi troops were defeated, U.S.
and British aircrafts have been using Turkish military base to
enforce a no-fly zone in northern Iraq, under the name of
protecting Iraqi Kurds there. Baghdad has been mainly ineffective
in its control over the region.
</P>
<P>
Fighting since 1984 for autonomy in southeast Turkey, PKK
militants often launched cross-border attacks on targets inside
Turkey from northern Iraq where they found shelter after the Gulf
War ended. (BC-Iraq-Turkey-Accusation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemeni President Ali Abdullah Saleh Friday welcomed
the international arbitration of his country's disputed island of
Greater Hanish with Eritrea and pledged to settle differences with
neighbors through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Calling the arbitration "a fair result," Saleh said peaceful
settlement of disputes and differences could help strengthen peace
and security in the region and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the London-based International Arbitration
Committee has reached a unanimous resolution in favor of Yemen's
sovereignty over the disputed island in the south of the Red Sea.
(BC-Yemen-Eritrea-Arbitration)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's semi-official Anatolia News Agency Friday
reported that Syria has promised to take measures to rein in
Turkey's Kurdish rebels on its territory.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified diplomatic sources, the agency said the
pledge was contained in an oral massage from Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad to his Turkish counterpart Suleyman Demirel,
conveyed by Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi who was on a
mediation mission.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of sheltering its rebel group
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) and threatened to use force against
rebel camps inside Syria. Syria denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that there are PKK sympathizers among the
people. So, we can not stop the PKK activities immediately, but we
banned the PKK organization and we are arresting the PKK
militants," Assad was quoted as saying in the oral message.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said Assad acknowledged that there were PKK
members in Syria and affirmed that he did not support them.
(BC-Turkey-Syria)

09/10/98 21:13 GMT

NNNN
05:11 05:11 g # PAB
</P>
