<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghanaian Opposition: No Need For New Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 9 (Xinhua) -- Ghana's main opposition New
Patriotic Party (NPP) said Friday that that there is no need to
purchase a new presidential plane because of the many other
important issues confronting the nation.
</P>
<P>
The NPP said in a statement that the 40 million U.S. Dollars
to spent on the new plane could be used to provide better health
and education facilities, among others, a special report reaching
here from Ghana News Agency (GNA) said.
</P>
<P>
It said the excuse that President Jerry John Rawlings travels
on the plane to canvass for investment is defeated by the
partisan nature of his huge entourage.
</P>
<P>
The president and his huge entourage on those trips have cost
this nation more than the investments they have brought in. Apart
from the investments being mainly extractive, it has brought in
people accused of introducing "apartheid" into Ghana, the GNA
quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If the President and his wife need to travel, there are
commercial planes aplenty. When Queen Elizabeth (of Britain) had
to go to Brunei, she flew in a commercial plane and we have not
heard of any harm coming to her..." the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The NPP doubted the genuineness of the assessment that the
presidential plane was not air worthy because it was over-aged.
</P>
<P>
The NPP is aware that South African President Nelson Mandela
flies around in a plane that is said to be 40 years old, which is
at least twice as old as the presidential plane which the Council
of State and other government supporters have named "the flying
coffin," the statement said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
